<HEADLINE> PfP Launches New Kind of Wargame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Budapest, May 11 (Xinhua) -- A new kind of "wargame" was
launched by Partnership for Peace (PfP) Monday, in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
Seven-hundred soldiers from 19 nations participated in the
military exercise, codenamed "Cooperative Lantern", which being
held in Balatonkenese, Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The wargame's main aim is to practice supervision of the
conducts of ceasefire and the maintanence of social
stability. Exchanges of prisoners of war and the extension of
humanitarian aid is also included in the practice.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, undertaken by a PfP program, will last five days.
</P>
<P>
The PfP is a brainchild of the 16-member North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), which set up the PfP in 1994 to help foster
ties with its former Warsaw Pact adversaries and other neutral
nations.
</P>
<P>
Another PfP-sponsored wargame, called Cooperative Jaguar, will
take place on May 18 in Denmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
