<HEADLINE> Vietnam Uses International Aid to Control AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is strengthening
international cooperation to control the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
A signing ceremony for "HIV/AIDS Prevention in Vietnam" was
held here on Monday, the Vietnam News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The nearly 525,000 U.S. dollar project, which is funded by the
United States Agency for International Development (USAID) will be
carried out from now to the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The project focuses on three principal areas, namely promoting
public health approaches, behavior change and risk reduction, and
private sector partnership in Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV)
and Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) prevention and
control.
</P>
<P>
It will be implemented by the National AIDS Committee of
Vietnam in collaboration with the Family Health International.
</P>
<P>
This is the first project within a framework agreement on
bilateral cooperation to control the spread of AIDS, which was
signed between Vietnam and the U.S. in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the U.S., Japan and the European Union have helped
Vietnam to promote the fight against HIV/AIDS by providing
condoms. Canada plans to provide 96,000 dollars to a project for
preventing AIDS and other sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
The German government has also planned to give another 400,000
U.S. dollars for the second phase of the Vietnam-German technical
assistance project to prevent HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) has
pledged to continue granting 750,000 dollars for a project to
strengthen AIDS management and the administration capacity of the
health network in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has played a part in an anti-AIDS project jointly
performed by Southeast Asian nations and China.
</P>
<P>
By May 9, 1998, Vietnam had detected 8,632 HIV victims,
including 1,202 AIDS patients. Six hundred and fourteen people
were reported to have died of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Intravenous drug users accounted for 65 percent of Vietnam's
HIV patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
