<HEADLINE> SBC to Acquire Ameritech in Largest Phone Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The SBC Communications Inc., the
No. 3 telecommunication giant, has agreed to purchase the Ameritech
Corp. for 62 billion U.S. dollars in a stock-swap deal, which would
be the second-largest merger in the telephone history.
</P>
<P>
According to an AP report reaching here from Chicago, the deal,
which was announced Monday, would create a powerhouse
communications company with operations in nearly every region of
this country, likely to pose as a potent rival to AT&AMP;T Corp., the
largest telecommunications firm in the country and to WorldCom
Inc. after its pending 37 billion dollar takeover of MCI
Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
After the completion of the deal, the combination of the two
companies would be second only to the pending 82 billion merger of
Travelers Group Inc. and Citicorp.
</P>
<P>
The proposed SBC-Ameritech combination would give the combined
company to be known as SBC 57 million phone lines, or nearly
one-third of the nation's total. By comparison, Bell Atlantic,
with operations along the East Coast, has 41 million phone lines.
</P>
<P>
The companies reportedly expect to save at least 1 billion
dollars with the combination.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Communications Commission, which must approve the
deal, had no immediate comment. But some consumer groups and major
rival giants expressed their strong opposition to the combination.
</P>
<P>
In a series of mergers and acquisitions since deregulation
began in 1996, communication companies have been scrambling to
outgun the competition by getting bigger and offering a wider
array of services, including cellular, local and long-distance
phone service.
</P>
<P>
SBC Communications, formerly called Southwestern Bell, has led
the way. It bought San Francisco-based Pacific Telesis Group a
year ago for 16.5 billion dollars and is working to complete its 5
billion dollar acquisition of Southern New England
Telecommunications Corp. of Connecticut.  
</P>
</TEXT>
