<HEADLINE> New French Army Chief Backs Arrest of Bosnian War Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The new chief of staff of the French
armed forces, General Jean-Pierre Kelche, said on Monday that the
arrest of war criminals in Bosnia is "an indispensable step in the
long process of return to civil peace" in that former Yugoslav
republic.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the daily Le Monde, Kelche, who took over
the post from General Jean-Philippe Douin last month in Bosnia,
also denied that French soldiers serving in the NATO Stabilization
Force (SFOR) in Bosnia were not active in arresting war criminals.
</P>
<P>
The southeast division SFOR in Bosnia, which is led by a French
officer, is not a French sector but a multinational one, and it
does not take orders from Paris but from the NATO command, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"SF0R is not for the mandate of carrying out operations to
search for and arrest these criminals.... That needs special units
for this type of mission with means of investigation and
particular actions at their disposals, and that they should be
perfectly coordinated at an international level," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that France will participate this kind of operations if
they are decided multilaterally instead of unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
'It is clear in my mind that the arrest of war criminals is, in
Bosnia, an indispensable step in the long process of return to
civil peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States last month accused a French military officer
serving in SFOR of deliberately damaging a NATO plan to arrest
Serb leader Radovan Karadzic by leaking the plan to the latter
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
France denied the accusation but admitted the relations between
the officer and Karadzic could have been "abnormal". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
