<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-11 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC to Hold Economic Cooperation Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Economic ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states will hold a meeting on May 18 in
Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, to bridge the gaps in tearing down their
customs barriers.
</P>
<P>
Adnan Al-Khdheir, director of the Arab and Gulf Economic
Cooperation Department at the Kuwaiti Finance Ministry, said
"unifying custom tariffs among GCC states will top issues in the
agenda."
</P>
<P>
He added that Kuwaiti Minister of Finance and Communications
Sheikh Ali Salem Al-Sabah will represent the Gulf emirate at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The issue of unifying customs tariffs was highly recommended
during last December's GCC summit in Kuwait. A solution to this is
expected to pave the way for the long-sought establishment of the
unified customs union and Gulf common market under an agreement
signed 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The six GCC states - Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab
Emirates, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain - have already agreed on the
categorization of over 900 goods out of 1,280 for tariff
reduction, after several rounds of talks over the past years.
</P>
<P>
However, they remain split on reducing the percentage of
national contribution to the added value of products of industrial
units. A technical committee met last week and recommended
lowering that percentage to 30 percent from the current 40
percent, but Saudi Arabia was opposed to the cut.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will discuss the proposed cut in their Riyadh
meeting.
</P>
<P>
A GCC secretariat source said last week that "lowering that
percentage means more factories will be exempted from customs and
such a move will motivate them into upgrading production."
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt this will increase trade among member
states and contribute to efforts to set up a common market," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Trade among GCC states has remained below 10 percent of their
total commercial exchanges of around 120 billion U.S. dollars a
year.
</P>
<P>
The Riyadh meeting would also discuss enhancing economic ties
among the GCC member states, Al-Khdheir said.
</P>
<P>
During the December summit, Kuwait submitted a working paper
regarding economic integration among GCC states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
