<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abrasion Found in 50 Percent of Boeing 737s Inspected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- In 50 percent of the Boeing 737
planes examined emergently, there was extensive wear in power
lines running through their wing fuel tanks, a U.S. Federal
Aviation Administration (FAA) official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
By Monday morning, 47 aircraft had been inspected and mechanics
found some signs of abrasion in half of the wiring bundles
examined, Jane Garvey, Federal Aviation Administrator, said on
NBC's "Today" show.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the FAA ordered operators to make emergency
inspections on Boeing 737-100 to 500 series planes for possible
fuel pump damage. The order was made three days after the agency
gave airlines up to a week to inspect their Boeing 737-100s and
200s for signs of wear in the wiring or the pipes that carry the
wires through the fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
The inspections would affect 15 percent, or some 270, of the
737s operating in the United States.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, mechanics inspecting a United Airlines 737 found
one wire bundle that showed signs of sparking in one spot and a
second area where the wires had been worn bare, most likely from
vibration over the plane's 50,000 hours in flight
</P>
<P>
Officials feared the mixture of fuel, air and electricity could
spark an explosion such as that which downed TWA Flight 800 in New
York in 1996, killing 230 aboard.
</P>
<P>
Boeing supported the action, which followed its own service
bulletin to aircraft owners on April 24. The manufacturer said it
was rushing repair kits to the airlines.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the FAA ordered inspections within 60 days for
Boeing 747 and 767 aircraft to make sure they had the necessary
protection around their fuel-tank wiring.
</P>
<P>
There are 1,088 Boeing 737s in the United States and 2,716
registered worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru-3: "Generally Peaceful" Voting in Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Voting for Monday's national and
local elections was held in a "generally peaceful and orderly
manner" with a heavy voter turnout across the country except for
some areas where polling was marred by violence and election
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commission on Elections, about 80 percent of
the 34 million voters turned out and cast their ballots to choose
a president, a vice president, 12 out of 24 senators, 260 members
of the House of Representatives and more than 17,000 local
officials and local councilors.
</P>
<P>
The voting was "generally peaceful and orderly", the Commission
on Elections said.
</P>
<P>
Early in the morning in Metro Manila, some people began to wait
outside their precincts even at 6 a.m. (22:00 GMT Sunday), one
hour before the voting starts. Poll watchers told Xinhua that
everything was orderly at dozens of precincts at a public
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
All major political parties assigned poll watchers to almost
every precinct and no fraud and cheating had been found in the
process of voting, the poll watchers said a few hours after the
voting started.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures showed that a total of 10 people were killed
all over the country in Monday's voting, bringing to 46 the death
toll in election-related violence incidents since election
campaigns began in February.
</P>
<P>
However, compared with the previous elections including the
ones held in 1992 and 1995, the polls may be the most peaceful and
orderly in the country's election history, poll watchers said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 elections, about 169 people were killed in election
related violence while in the 1995 senate elections 210 people
died.
</P>
<P>
To ensure "honest, peaceful and orderly elections," the
government has identified 425 towns and municipalities as
"sensitive areas" and deployed 116,000 troops and policemen across
the country.
</P>
<P>
A failure of elections had been declared in seven towns in
Lanao del Sur province, five towns and cities in Maguindanao
province and four precincts in Lanao de Norte province, affecting
144,000 people.
</P>
<P>
"We have reports that commission officials in Davao had
declared failure of elections," Commission on Elections
commissioner Evalyn Fetalino said, adding that the commission had
the right to re-schedule a special election as quickly as possible
in the above areas.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the confirmed reports of failure of elections,
buying of votes, missing of names, cases of disfranchisement and
double registrations of voters were also reported in central
Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Voters confirmed to police officials that leaders of at least
three gubernatorial candidates in the Lao del Sur were paying
voters from 300 to 400 pesos (about 10 U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the voting ended at 3 p.m. (7:00 GMT), the
counting started at the precinct level and are ongoing in some
areas in Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
The latest exit poll conducted by the private radio station
DZRH showed vice President Joseph Estrada, candidate of the Laban
ng Makabayang masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipinos
Masses) far ahead of the other 9 presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that 34.6 percent of the 41,840 voters surveyed
across the country said they voted for the 61-year-old former
movie star.
</P>
<P>
After casting his vote in a Manila suburb precinct, Estrada,
surrounded by a large crowd of supporters, said he would win the
election by "a landslide victory."
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Jose de Venecia, who was anointed by President
Fidel Ramos as the standard bearer of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party
in the presidential race, trailed with 16.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other main contenders include former Manila mayor Alfredo Lim
and senator Raul Roco of Akson Demokratiko (Democratic Action).
</P>
<P>
After the counting at the precinct level, election inspectors
will turn over the election returns to the municipal or city
level. The total election returns will be recorded and tabulated
and then given to the provincial level.
</P>
<P>
The forms will then be forwarded to the House of
Representatives for the counting for presidential and vice
presidential positions, while the Commission on Elections will
count the votes for the congressional posts.
</P>
<P>
The process is expected to take four weeks. But a private
watchdog organization conducting a quick count under the
accreditation of the Commission on Elections said it can release
the final results within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
As no candidate is expected to get majority support in the
final results, it is too early to say who will win the presidency,
analysts said. More violence could take place before the winning
bet is officially proclaimed, they warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
