<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-11 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Reiterates Stand on Cyprus' Missile Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said Monday that its position
on the Cypriot government's plan to deploy Russian-made S-300
missiles on the divided island remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"Our views on the deployment of the S-300 missiles have been
put forward on various occasions in the past and there has not
been any change in Turkey's position on that issue," Turkish
Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli said at a weekly
news briefing Monday,
</P>
<P>
Turkey's military has vowed that it will take all necessary
measures to prevent the missiles from entering the island,
underlining that the deployment will threaten Turkey's security.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli dismissed as groundless recent Greek press reports,
which claimed that Ankara would make concessions on the Cyprus
issue if the missiles were really deployed.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports have said that the S-300 missile system
might be deployed in Cyprus later this year under a
Russian-Cypriot deal signed last year.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Turkish Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki
Karadayi's visit to Moscow scheduled for next week, Atacanli
said, "it is an important part of our policy to improve relations
with the Russian Federation."
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to disclose what measures Turkey would
take if Russia insisted on going ahead with the missile deal.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the missile issue will top the agenda of
Karadayi visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkish troops
landed and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece in 1974.
</P>
<P>
Turkey firmly supports Turkish Cypriots who unilaterally
declared in 1983 a "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which
was recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
At present, Turkey and Greece have stationed heavily armed
troops on the small island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Denies Backing Angolan Separatists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 11 (Xinhua) -- France Monday formally denied an
accusation by a regional military official of Angola that it is
backing the separatist movement of the Angolan oil-rich enclave of
Cabinda.
</P>
<P>
The vice-chairman of defense of Cabinda, General Futi, said in
an interview with the weekly Folha-8 published in Luanda on May 5
that the chief of the separatist Front of Liberation of the
Enclave of Cabinda is living in France.
</P>
<P>
France is providing a "more than just moral" support to the
Cabinda separatists, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot but give a formal denial to this kind of estimations
which are groundless and aimed at discrediting our policy toward
Angola," said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
The French oil group Elf-Aquitaine is having tremendous
interests in the oil resources in Angola and its neighboring
country of Congo Republic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
