<HEADLINE> Britain to Offer Zimbabwe 12 Million Pounds Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The British government has set
aside 12 million Pounds sterling for development programs in
Zimbabwe this year, British High Commissioner Peter Longworth
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
After paying a courtesy call on Zimbabwe's acting President
Simon Muzenda Peter Longworth told the Zimbabwe News Agency that
the money was allocated to poverty elimination, improvement of
water supplies and education.
</P>
<P>
"Our relationship is not based on the land issue. I have had a
very good conversation with Zimbabwean Minister of Lands and
Agriculture Kumbirai Kangai, and explained our position (on the
country's land reform) clearly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Zimbabwean government has already designated
1,500 farms or five million hectares for compulsory acquisition
for the new resettlement program. The land policy has been
criticized by the British government and some other west
countries.
</P>
<P>
Longworth said Britain and Zimbabwe shared the same objectives
and were trying to establish an arrangement where the land
redevelopment program was directed to the elimination of poverty.
</P>
<P>
He said during the half-hour discussion he assured Muzenda
that Britain had a strong interest in working side by side with
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very strong trading relationship. Today a group of
British business people has come in to see what kind of business
they can do in Zimbabwe," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said three missions would be coming this year, including
one from the Leicester Chamber of Commerce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
