<HEADLINE> S. Africa Speeds up Implementation of Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa hoped to
implement 44 bilateral investment treaties by the end of this
financial year, the Trade and Industry Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Such agreements provided guarantees that foreign investments
would not be nationalized willy-nilly, or expropriated, thus
reassuring individual investors that their money would be safe,
South African Press Association quoted deputy director Robert
Moodie as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This solid collection of treaties...indicate that we are
moving progressively ahead in providing an ever stronger base for
foreign direct investment," Moodie said.
</P>
<P>
Moodie said eight such agreements had been put into effect
since 1994, when the program began in earnest.
</P>
<P>
The process to implement these treaties had since been
streamlined, enabling the treaties to reach the binding stage
more quickly.
</P>
<P>
The eight treaties already in place were concluded with China,
Germany, France, Denmark, Cuba, South Korea, Switzerland, and
Austria.
</P>
<P>
Several others were in various stages of implementation with
countries including Iran, Italy, Britain, Canada, the
Netherlands, Finland, Sweden and Russia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
