<HEADLINE> WHO Director-General Nominee Determined to Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The Director-General Nominee of the
World Health Organization (WHO) Mrs Gro Harlem Brundtland has said
that she is determined to fight against tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland was nominated to the post by the 101st session of
the WHO Executive Board during its session last January. The 191
WHO member states will formally elect her on May 13.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed by the situation in which children in the developing
world are being drawn into smoking, Brundtland said legislation
prohibiting children from smoking similar to that in much of the
West is needed in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco has to be fought now because the children and young
people are becoming influenced now," she said before the start of
the week-long 51st World Health Assembly, WHO's highest governing
body.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to tell the world why it is dangerous and give
advice on how to deal with it on a regulatory fashion because
governments have to pass laws like we have done in Europe and the
United States," said Brundtland.
</P>
<P>
According to WHO's annual report released here Monday, in 1997
different cancers killed 6.2 million people around the world. Lung
cancer alone killed 1.1 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
