<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-11 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Spokesman on Turkish Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government is trying to
draw world's attention to the "direction of Turkey which made
threats against Cyprus" as more countries expressed concern about
Cyprus' decision to deploy Russia-made S-300 missiles.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing Monday, government spokesman Christos
Stylianides said "the Cyprus government has clearly expressed its
views on the issue to those expressing concern about
destabilization and those who advise against the deployment of the
S-300 missiles."
</P>
<P>
"Turkish threats with regard to the government decision to
deploy the Russian defense missile system S-300 on the island are
well known and so is the reaction of certain circles of the
international community," Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "those expressing concern should look to
the direction of the Turkish government and not to the government
of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated the Cypriot government position that
the S-300 will not be deployed if there is an agreement for
demilitarzation of the island or if there is substantial progress
toward a comprehensive solution of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974, when Turkey landed its
troops on the island and took over the northern third in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has so far maintained around 45,000 troops in northern
Cyprus, which was declared unilaterally by Turkish Cypriots in
1983 as "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," recognized only by
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government decided last year to purchase Russian
S-300 surface-to-air missiles to upgrade its defense capability.
The missiles are scheduled to be delivered later this year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reacted strongly to the deal, threatening to block
the delivery and, if that fails, to destroy the missiles.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has criticized Ankara for its threats, but echoed by
the European Union, it has also warned Cyprus against deployment,
which it considers as "counter-productive."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on recent discussions between U.S. State Department
Special Co-ordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller and Greek Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos concerning military overflights in
Cyprus, the spokesman said there have been coordinations between
the Nicosia and Athens governments.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos "always acts within the joint strategy between Greece
and Cyprus, concerning issues relating to the Cyprus problem,"
Stylianides noted.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Greek daily "Kathimerini" Sunday,
Miller expressed serious concern with the possibility of a "hot
summer" in Cyprus and the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
He noted that to avoid any negative developments the U.S. is
studying a recent suggestion by Pangalos for the creation of a
no-fly zone of Greek and Turkish military planes over Cyprus, with
guarantees from the U.S. and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization to which both Greece and Turkey belong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
