<HEADLINE> World Automotive Industry Acquisition at 28 bln </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- World automotive industry underwent
more than 700 merger or acquisition deals with a value of around
28 billion U.S. dollars last year, according to a survey published
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The annual automotive global deals survey by accountancy group
Price Waterhouse said that the factors leading to the acquisition
deals were Asia's economic turmoil, global over-capacity and poor
prospects for growth.
</P>
<P>
It said that Europe was the main focus of the merger process
last year, with acquisition activity jumping 50 percent from 10 to
15 billion dollars, covering 371 individual transactions.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that as the overall outlook of the markets in
Western Europe and North America is now flat at best, the pace of
consolidation will quicken throughout 1998 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that the industry has to continue to globalize
in order to contain costs, requiring investments in technology and
organizational improvements by vehicle distributors as well as
component makers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
