<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Revenue Collection to Fall Short of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's revenue collections for
this fiscal year which ends in June are expected to stand at 810
Ugandan Shillings (675 million U.S. Dollars), 30 billion
Shillings (2.5 million Dollars) less than the projected target.
</P>
<P>
In his 1997/98 budget speech last June, Financial Minister,
Jehoash Mayanja-Nkangi set a target of 700 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A report carried by Monday's East African weekly put the blame
on a number of factors including extreme weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
It said heavy rains across east Africa in September 1997
caused devastation to communication, destroyed crops, lowered
crop yields and prevented farmers from transporting produce to
the markets.
</P>
<P>
This revenue shortfall has also been blamed on global rise in
crude oil prices and the smuggling of petroleum and petroleum
products. The poor performance of imports and value added tax are
also held responsible for the decrease.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's revenue collections have been on the increase since
the creation of the Uganda revenue authority in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991/92 financial year, some 180 billion Shillings (150
million U.S. Dollars) was collected. In the following years, it
rises by leaps and bounds. The revenue collection in the 1996/97
fiscal year hit the record high of 733 billion Shillings (610
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Uganda, which recently received a debt relief of 350 million
Dollars under an international initiative targeted at debtor
countries with a good financial management record, has a total
external debt burden of more than 3.6 billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Uganda will get debt relief totalling 650 million
Dollars from its external creditors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
