<HEADLINE> UN Chief Expresses Deep Regret Over India's Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Monday expressed deep regret over India's announced
nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
India announced on Monday that it had conducted three
underground nuclear tests in the western desert state of
Rajasthan.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, Annan said, "
for quite some time now, there has been a de facto moratorium on
nuclear testing. The moratorium and the successful conclusion of
the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) in September 1996
are seen by the international community as setting a norm with
regard to nuclear non-proliferation,"
</P>
<P>
Noting that India is not a signatory to the CTBT, Annan said he is
very concerned that the latest testing is inconsistent with the
pattern which has been firmly endorsed by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General called on all States for maximum
restraint with a view to facilitating nuclear non-proliferation
and nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
He strongly supports accelerated measures of nuclear
disarmament, cessation of all nuclear tests by all States and
strengthening of the nuclear non-proliferation regime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
