<HEADLINE> Uganda to Install 20 Radio-TV Transmitting Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is planning to make big
stride in broadcasting by installing over the next two years 20
stations capable of transmitting FM radio and TV signals at once.
</P>
<P>
According to a report carried by the latest issue of East
African, a weekly published in Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania, the
new stations will be able to send signals to over 70 percent of
the country's population and set new standards of sound and
picture quality for east Africa.
</P>
<P>
This broadcasting expansion project is to be carried out in
two phases and will cost some 4.5 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The first phase, likely to be launched in May, involves
setting up FM stations in 12 major towns while the second phase
involves the installation of smaller stations.
</P>
<P>
The number of FM stations across the country will shoot up
from nine at present to 29 on the completion of the project,
giving Uganda the highest FM coverage in eastern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The project is widely expected to boost Radio Uganda and
Uganda Television revenues, which have been on the decline since
the setting up of private FM radio stations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
