<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEU Ministerial Meeting Begins in Rhodes, Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rhodes, Greece, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-six Foreign and
Defense Ministers from 28 countries of the Western European Union
(WEU) began later Monday their two-day meeting on the Greek
southeastern Aegean island of Rhodes to discuss the organization's
future role and how to upgrade its operational capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the joint session of foreign and defense ministers,
WEU Secretary-General Jose Cutilheiro said that WEU now had an
important and clearly defined role to play in the European
Security and defense architecture.
</P>
<P>
He added that with this new strengthening both of their
military and their overall political-military structure, added to
the concepts and plans they had already developed, WEU was better
placed than ever to shoulder the responsibility of political
control and strategic direction for a European-led Petersberg
operation, that was crisis management operations in which North
Americans would not wish to involve themselves directly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos stressed
that the WEU's aim should be to contribute by all means to the
enhancement of security and stability by ensuring a commensurate
European participation in collective defense and by an active
engagement in conflict prevention and crisis management in Europe
and elsewhere befitting the Union's political and economic weight.
</P>
<P>
He said that the WEU's most important task remained to gather
the political will required for Europe to shape a truly European
defense identity which he also describes as "a challenge" for the
WEU, European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Greece, which is currently holding the WEU's six-month rotating
presidency, became a full WEU member in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1955, the WEU, the military arm of the EU, now has
10 full members which consist of Belgium, Britain, France,
Germany, Greece, Italy, Luxemburg, the Netherlands, Portugal and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
The WEU also has three associate members that include Iceland,
Norway and Turkey; five observers made up of Austria, Denmark,
Ireland, Sweden and Finland; 10 associate partners from Bulgaria,
the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Latvia, Lithuania, Poland,
Romania, Slovakia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
The last WEU ministerial meeting was held in Erfurt, Germany,
in November 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
