<HEADLINE> Zambia-Egypt Trade to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's participation in the Common
Market for Southern and Eastern Africa (COMESA) will produce
increased trade opportunities between the north African country
and Zambia, the Zambia Association of Chambers of Commerce and
Industry (ZACCI) said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
ZACCI Chairman Goerge Chabwera said that Egypt's joining the
regional trade group will provide a huge market to Aambia and
other COMESA member countries.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has already exported copper and other commodities to
Egypt and his country's export potential is likely to increase
tremendously if Egypt joins COMESA, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's trade terms are more favorable than those prevailing
in the region thereby giving Zambia an alternative cheaper
market, Chabwera said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambia's products are still finding it hard to enter
markets like that in Zimbabwe because of the existing tariff
barriers. But this is not likely to be the case with the Egyptian
market.
</P>
<P>
He urged the COMESA secretariat to expand on its information
capacity in order to woo more trading partners as an important
step to integrate COMESA into the global market.
</P>
<P>
A draft agreement on the accession of Egypt to the COMESA
treaty was concluded here last week by an Egyptian government
delegation and the COMESA secretariat in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will be admitted into COMESA at the group's next
summit to be held next month in Kinshasa, the capital of the
Democratic Republic of Congo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
