<HEADLINE> Caspian Environment Protection Fund to Be Set up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 11 (Xinhua) -- A Caspian Sea environment protection
fund is to be set up with the financing of the U.N. Development
Program (UNDP), the European Union (EU) and the World Bank (WB).
</P>
<P>
U.N. resident coordinator in Iran Michael V.D. Schulenburg made
the announcement Monday in Ramsar in the northern province of
Mazandaran, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator said the fund, with an initial capital of 50
million U.S. dollars, is to start operation in June.
</P>
<P>
He said that 12 million dollars would come from the U.N., 6
million from the EU, and the rest from the WB, adding that various
Caspian-based oil exploration companies were also required to
donate.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea was not a regional issue, but a global one, and
the whole world was duty-bound to preserve the ecosystem of the
world's largest inland sea, the U.N. official stressed.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of oil drilling and exploitation in the
region, the Caspian has been facing a growing serious
environmental threat as thousands of tons of various chemical
substances are discharged into the sea every year.
</P>
<P>
Experts have warned that pollution from and competition among
the littoral states in oil exploitation will damage the ecosystem
and finally destroy the natural resources in and around the sea,
particularly the caviar, a delicacy known as "black pearl."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
