<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Kills 150 S. Leone Junta Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
ECOMOG Monday killed about 150 troops of Sierra Leone's fleeing
junta forces and allied rebels in a battle in the east of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The force also captured another 30 of the anti-government
troops, according to a British Broadcasting Corporation report
monitored here.
</P>
<P>
The battle started on April 30 when ECOMOG forces launched a
full scale offensive across the border from neighboring Guinea
into Kailahon District.
</P>
<P>
The district in eastern Sierra Leone is the traditional
stronghold of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF), which
became allied to the junta shortly after the coup a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Both the junta and RUF were driven out of the capital Freetown
by ECOMOG in mid-February, and the remnants retreated to the
east, promising to fight back from the countryside.
</P>
<P>
A mopping up exercise has since been carried out.
</P>
<P>
After Monday's heavy fighting, some other junta members fled
across the border into Liberia, the report said, quoting a
commander of the civil defense group Kamajors, which fight
alongside with ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajor director of war said soon his men will be pursuing
the junta and RUF troops into Liberian territory because "it is
being used as a safe haven".
</P>
<P>
He also warned any attempt by flying rebels to attack towns or
villages in Guinea will be disastrous.  
</P>
</TEXT>
