<HEADLINE> Iran Warns Against Entry of Jellyfish to Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 11 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian official warned on
Monday that the entry of jellyfish from the Black Sea to the
Caspian will destroy the caviar industry in the world largest
inland sea.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the official news agency IRNA in Ramsar in the
northern province of Mazandaran, director of the Sustainable
Development and Environment Protection Organization Mohammad Taqi
Farhur said that jellyfish had destroyed caviar industry in the
Black Sea over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
He said that a number of jellyfish have recently been observed
in the Caspian, adding that the fish found their way to the
Caspian through tankers, which carried oil from the Caspian to the
Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian meets 90 percent of the world's demand for caviar
and Iran exported some 105 tons of caviar during the past Iranian
year ended March 20, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
