<HEADLINE> Air Tanzania Refutes Reports on Landing Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The Air Tanzania Corporation
(ATC) has refuted media reports that one of its planes diverted
from the runway and got stuck in the mud at the Mwanza airport
when it was landing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
ATC managing director, Dominic Rwenhumbiza, said in a
statement issued Monday that the plane, christened "Serengeti",
landed at the airport as scheduled after getting clearance from
the control room.
</P>
<P>
Rwenhumbiza explained that the pilot, captain John Mturi, was
assured by the control tower that although the runway was wet
following a downpour, normal landing was possible.
</P>
<P>
On touching the tarmac, the statement said, the pilot found
that the runway was submerged by water which was four to five
feet deep. He waited for the water to drain before taxiing to the
airport building where passengers disembarked using a normal
ladder.
</P>
<P>
He said the plane was not stuck in the mud and the passengers
did not use emergency rescue ladder.
</P>
<P>
Since the runway was wet, the aircraft was not cleared to take
off to Kigali as scheduled and had a night stop in Mwanza and
left for Kigali at 09:00 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
The plane came back to Mwanza and then returned to Dar es
Salaam airport at 02:15 p.m., according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement went on to say that it was not true that the
plane had to circle for two hours as reported by some newspapers,
noting that technically it was impossible because it would have
sought an alternative landing port or flown back.
</P>
<P>
Dar es Salaam newspapers reported Monday that passengers
aboard an Air Tanzania Corporation (ATC) Boeing-737 had a narrow
escape after the plane slipped into mud Sunday at an airport in
the Mwanza Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
