<HEADLINE> IRNA Chief Acquitted by Press Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Fereydoun Verdinejad, managing
director of the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) and
publisher of the moderate daily newspaper Iran, was acquitted on
Monday by a special press court after a four-hour deliberation.
</P>
<P>
IRNA reported that two charges were brought against Verdinejad
in the press court, which works under the jury system, but the
IRNA chief "outright rejected" the accusations.
</P>
<P>
Parliament member Ahmad Rasoulinejad accused the Iran daily of
publishing a caricature which was believed to have resemblance
with him. But the court ruled in Verdinejad's favor.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Rasoulinejad, a conservative parliamentarian,
strongly criticized former Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani
for supporting Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, who was
temporally detained on embezzlement charges.
</P>
<P>
Another charge against Verdinejad was the publication of news
related to the country's police, which claimed that the
dissemination of the news about its activities in the newspaper
would weaken the force's ability, IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
Defending the newspaper, Verdinejad told the court that his
paper was fully prepared to assist the police in strengthening
the foundation of the country's security.
</P>
<P>
Verdinejad started the publication of the pro-government
newspaper Iran in 1994, which served as one of the main
supporters of President Mohammad Khatami after he was elected last
May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
