<HEADLINE> VVD Gets One More Seat From CDA in Dutch Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The People's Party for Freedom and
Democracy (VVD) got one more seat from the Christian Democratic
Appeal (CDA) in the Dutch general election, according to the final
result announced by the election committee on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The People's Party for Freedom and Democracy, a major coalition
with the Labor Party, was awarded 38 seats in the 150-seat lower
house of the Dutch parliament when an intermediate result was made
public last Wednesday. It now has 39 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Christian Democratic Appeal now has 28 seats, Dutch
television NOS-TT reported.
</P>
<P>
The number of parliamentary seats for the Labor Party and the
minor coalition Democrats 66 remained unchanged at 45 and 14
respectively.
</P>
<P>
They are followed by the ecological group Green Left with 11
seats.
</P>
<P>
A total of 22 parties took part in last Wednesday's general
election, the 17th of its kind after World War II, and 13 of them
did not get any seat in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Persistent drizzles caused a low turnout rate. Official
figures showed that only 73.2 percent of the 11.7 million eligible
voters went to cast their ballots on the election day.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch public is waiting for the formation of the next
government, of which the Labor Party and the People's Party for
Freedom and Democracy are certain to be in.
</P>
<P>
The Democrats 66 pronounced that if it lost too many of its
seats it would not join in the coalition again. The minor
coalition had 24 seats from the previous election and lost almost
half of them this time. It is still to announce whether to join
the new coalition.
</P>
<P>
The three-party coalition, known as the purple politics, that
took office four years ago, won solid praise from the Dutch public
for its practical economic policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
