<HEADLINE> Former Govt Soldiers in Court on Genocide Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan military has opened
the genocide trials of former government soldiers who were
involved in the 1994 genocide of Tutsis and opposition Hutus.
</P>
<P>
Second-lieutenant Pierre Bizimana and sergeant Aloys Mazimpaka
appeared in Butare war crimes tribunal this Monday morning to
respond to several charges relating to the atrocities they
committed during the 1994 bloodbath that claimed over one million
lives.
</P>
<P>
The two soldiers are the first ex-government soldiers to be
tried for genocide crimes since trials began here in December
1996, Rwanda News Agency quoted official sources in Kigali as
saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of ex-government soldiers in connection
with the massacres that rocked Rwanda for about 100 days was
still unknown. When genocide broke out here, the presidential
guard of late President Juvenal Habyarimana and other ex-FAR were
on the helm of the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
The two soldiers were from northwestern Rwanda, home to late
President Habyarimana, and were based at Butare college cadet
offices (ESO).
</P>
<P>
The defendants were assisted by a Belgian lawyer, Jerry Jeert
hired by the non-governmental organizations Lawyers Without
Borders based in Brussels. Seventeen genocide survivors were also
present at the opening of the trial, but were not assisted by any
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
After the military prosecutor had read out charges to the
accused, the defense counsel requested the postponement of the
trial claiming that he did not give enough time to examine the
files of his clients. The trail will resume on May 24, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, over 130,000 genocide suspects are detained in
Rwandan jails. About 300 last year were judged, with about 100
death sentences.
</P>
<P>
The first 22 genocide culprits were publicly executed on May
24,1998 and more are expected to follow either in public or
secret places, government officials indicated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
