<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-11 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Suggests Draft Seminary Students to Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor Party
leader Ehud Barak submitted Monday his bill to Knesset
(parliament) Speaker Dan Tichon, calling for the draft of seminary
students (yashiva) to the defense forces.
</P>
<P>
Terming his intention as not against Israel's Jewish yashiva
students, Barak said the country's defense requires equal
participation of all young people from different religious groups.
</P>
<P>
In his bill, Barak suggests that 700 Jewish yashiva students be
exempted from military service each year.
</P>
<P>
These students, who can be exempted from service permanently,
must remain in yashiva full-time until 25. If they drop out of
yashiva before the age, they should be subject to the draft.
</P>
<P>
Drafting yashiva students into the defense forces is not only
a religious but also a political issue in Israel because the
yashiva students have been exempted from serving in the defense
forces.
</P>
<P>
During the Sunday cabinet meeting, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu raised this issue and instructed to set up a committee
headed by the retired Supreme Court Justice Zvi Tal to study the
issue to prevent it from turning into a political crisis in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
