<HEADLINE> S. Leone Breaks Silence on British Firms' Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone Monday broke silence on
the arms deal involving British firm Sandline, saying the weapons
brought in by the company were not used in fighting against the
legitimate government but the military junta.
</P>
<P>
The British parliament has recently become boiled when
ministers were briefed about Sandline's involvement in Sierra
Leone and whether the arms shipment was in breach of the United
Nations arms embargo on the west African country.
</P>
<P>
However, the Sierra Leonean side ruled out the involvement of
the British government in the arms deal, according to a British
Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here.
</P>
<P>
"The president (Ahmed Tejan Kabbah) entered into an
arrangement with Sandline. I don't believe he consulted with the
British government in any formal way," said Information Minister
J. Spencer.
</P>
<P>
He argued the arms and ammunition were used to restore the
legitimate government ousted in a coup last May, thus the case
had nothing to do with the U.N. arms sanction.
</P>
<P>
The British government should be proud even if it was involved
in the deal, the minister stated.
</P>
<P>
He said the weapons probably have been used by ECOMOG, the
sub-regional peacekeeping force which dislodged the junta and
helped restore Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
Under the original agreement, the minister said, the Sierra
Leonean government would allow Sandline to prospect minerals in
the country.
</P>
<P>
He refused to say whether there is any change in the agreement
as Sandline has to deliver what it should have delivered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
