<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Urges U.S. to Press Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia Monday called on
the United States to exert pressure on Israel in an effort to
revive the stalled Middle East peace process, according to Saudi
Press Agency reports from Saudi Red Sea coast city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
The agency said quoting Saudi Information Minister Fuad Faresi
as saying that a cabinet meeting chaired by King Fahd "discussed
the faltering Middle East peace process and ways to reactivating
it according to what was agreed in Madrid, Oslo and Washington."
</P>
<P>
The minister said the cabinet urged "the co-sponsors, the
U.S. and Russia, in particular the United States, to make maximum
efforts to push forward the peace process on the right track."
</P>
<P>
The call came amidst what was seen as playing with time by
Israeli right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to stifle the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton was to be hosting a meeting in
Washington on Monday with Netanyahu and the Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat, but the plan was blocked as Netanyahu refused to
agree with a new U.S. initiative to hand over 13.1 percent of the
West Bank to the Palestinians to end the 14-month-long deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. peace coordinator Dennis Ross left Israel Sunday after
meeting with both the Israeli and Palestinian leaders and
officially told Arafat the Washington meeting slated for Monday
was delayed.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Arab League (AL) on Monday also
urged the sponsors of the Middle East peace to confront with
firmness the policy of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid warned in a statement
of potential dire consequences of the prevailing atmosphere of
pessimism and frustration in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
