Wandira Kazibwe said here Monday that some 45 percent of Uganda's
population is malnourished.
</P>
<P>
She made this statement when addressing the opening ceremony
of a two-day workshop on food security and agricultural policies.
</P>
<P>
Food shortages in Uganda, she said is a result of bad weather
conditions caused by the El-Nino phenomenon and lack of
agricultural technology.
</P>
<P>
She called for more and better policies to ensure food
security in the country.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said there is need for the growth of food
production to exceed population growth if the people hope to
realize higher incomes and better life.
</P>
<P>
The major challenges facing the agricultural sector, she
added, include food security policy, agricultural technology,
marketing output and job creation by the sector.
</P>
<P>
She predicted that as many as 2.5 million jobs will be created
if the farming families become commercially oriented.
</P>
<P>
She also called for a change in people's nutritional structure
and urged investors to vigorously engage in more agricultural
trading and processing by setting up food processing units in
rural areas. 
</P>
