<HEADLINE> Leaders Top House Fund-Raisers for Mid-Term Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The Republican and Democratic
leaders of the U.S. House of Representatives are the top
fund-raisers so far for the November elections, according to the
Federal Election Commission (FEC).
</P>
<P>
The FEC reported Monday that Speaker Newt Gingrich, a
Republican, took in 3.8 million U.S. dollars between January 1,
1997, and March 31, 1998, while House Minority Leader Richard A.
Gephardt, a Democrat, took in 3.1 million dollars during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
Following them were Representative Loretta Sanchez, a Democrat,
and former Representative Bob Dornan, a Republican, each with 1.8
million dollars. Dornan, who is running to get back the seat he
lost to Sanchez in a hotly contested 1996 race, has raised more
money than any other challenger for a House seat. But he faces a
primary for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
The House member with the most cash on hand as of March 31 was
Representative David Dreier, a Republican, with three million
dollars, followed by Gephardt, with 1.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the Senate side, Senator Alfonse D'Amato, a Republican, had
the most money on hand as of March 31 -- 10.6 million dollars. One
of three Democrats vying for the nomination to challenge him,
Representative Charles Schumer, had 8.2 million dollars to spend.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Senate and House candidates reported taking in 338.2
million dollars during the 15-month period. That's 41 million
dollars, or 14 percent, more than they raised during the
comparable period in 1995-96.  
</P>
</TEXT>
