<HEADLINE> Cyprus Predicts Higher Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
predicted Monday that the country's economic growth rate this year
is expected to reach 4.5 percent, up 2 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that meanwhile the fiscal deficit, which accounted for
5 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) in 1997, is expected
to shrink in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the remarks at an annual meeting of the Employers
and Industrialists Federation, which opened in Nicosia Monday. He
said that if employers and the workers' unions exercise necessary
restraint, unemployment and inflation rates are expected to fall
to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Referring to tourism, whose income reached 1.6 billion
U.S. dollars last year and accounts for over 20 percent of the
country's GDP, Clerides said measures would be taken this year to
enrich the island's tourism services to attract more middle- and
upper-class tourists.
</P>
<P>
Clerides stressed that the government's goal was not only to
fulfill the Maastricht Treaty criteria, but also to achieve the
harmonization with the European Union (EU), social justice,
economic stability and development.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty, which went into effect in 1993, aims to
create a political alliance and single currency in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, with a per capita income of 12,800 dollars, began
accession talks with the EU in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
