<HEADLINE> IPE's Natural Gas Futures Break Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Volumes of trade on the
International Petroleum Exchange's (IPE) Natural Gas futures
contract reached 3535 lots, a new record on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It is equivalent to more than 106 million therms or 50 percent
more than total UK daily natural gas consumption, according to an
announcement by the IPE.
</P>
<P>
Monday's trade was concentrated in the October and November
contracts and the previous record was 2705 lots on 23 December
last year.
</P>
<P>
Richard Ward, Executive Vice President for Business Development
said: "This new record is a further sign of the contract's
importance to the industry."
</P>
<P>
"Natural Gas futures have become a key part of the physical
market place, not just as a hedging mechanism but also as a price
reference tool for deals," he added.
</P>
<P>
The IPE said that open interest for Natural Gas futures also
set a new record of 22,450 lots.
</P>
<P>
Natural Gas futures were launched by the IPE on 31 January
1997.
</P>
<P>
The contract has developed into a key indicator of price trends
in the UK market and a number of physical and swap deals have been
linked to the IPE Natural Gas futures settlement price.  
</P>
