<HEADLINE> Wildlife Program Covers 7 More Tanzanian Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Seven more villages in the
south Tanzania's Ruvuma region has been placed under a wildlife
conservation program so as to fight poachers, Shihata reported.
</P>
<P>
Ruvuma regional game officer, Esau Sonoko, told the Tanzania
News Agency in the Songea district of the region Monday that the
villages, bordering the Selous Game Reserve, the world's largest,
used to be frequented by poachers.
</P>
<P>
He named villages which have been newly included in the
conservation program as Lutukila, Ifinga, Mtelawamwai, in the
Songea district, and Liwangula, Ngapa, Namwinyu and Namindu in
the Tunduru district.
</P>
<P>
The program is co-sponsored by German organization GTZ and the
Tanzanian government, he said, adding that 18 villages have
already been listed in the program.
</P>
<P>
Several villagers have been trained and given ammunition to
combat poachers.
</P>
<P>
Sonoko said the involvement of villagers in the Selous Game
Reserve conservation program has borne fruits, citing the growth
of tourist hunters and decrease in poaching incidents. 
</P>
