<HEADLINE> Protection Pact to Boost UK Investment in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- A recent agreement between Uganda
and the United Kingdom to ensure protection of each other's
investment in either territory is to boost British investment in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
This pact is aimed at protecting UK investments as Britain has
some 503 licensed projects in Uganda while this former British
colony has comparatively few investments on British soil.
</P>
<P>
This agreement outlines the terms under which compensations
will be paid out in case of losses resulting from
nationalization, expropriation, armed conflicts, state of
national emergency or insurrection.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, nationals or companies of either country
whose investments suffer losses shall be accorded the same
treatments as nationals of that state as regards restitution,
indemnification, compensation or other settlement.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for the unrestricted transfer of investment
returns from either country.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Mugabi, an official with the Uganda Investment
Authority, said,"with the signing of this agreement, we expect to
get more investors from the United Kingdom, because even before
this development Britain was the leading investor in Uganda."
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been engaged in an international campaign to
attract investment, but many investors have been skeptical,
citing the 1972 expulsion of Asians from the country and the
expropriation of their properties.
</P>
<P>
Although the expelled Asians repossessed their property some
time later, quite a number of investors demand government
guarantees that their investments would be protected from
arbitrary military take-overs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
