<HEADLINE> FSA Reaches Agreement With Sumitomo on Hamanaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The Financial Services Authority
(FSA) Monday announced an agreement with Sumitomo Corporation of
Japan in relation to the copper-trading activities of Yasuo
Hamanaka.
</P>
<P>
In reaching this agreement, the FSA has decided that no purpose
would be served by further consideration of possible use of its
enforcement powers against Sumitomo in relation to Hamanaka,
former head of its Non-Ferrous Metals Department.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo recognizes the part played by the FSA investigations
in causing Hamanaka finally, in June 1996, to confess to 10 years
unauthorized trading and fraud.
</P>
<P>
Without admission of any liability, Sumitomo now agrees to pay
5,000,000 pounds to the FSA for its investigation and other costs.
</P>
<P>
In reaching the agreement, the FSA recognizes that Sumitomo has
given prompt, valuable and extensive cooperation following
Hamanaka's confession in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
On 13 june 1996, Sumitomo announced the dismissal of Hamanaka
and the discovery of his unauthorized trading over a 10 year
period at a cost to Sumitomo of 2.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sumitomo agrees to continue to assist the FSA in the
finalization of its investigations.
</P>
<P>
The FSA said that it has also received substantial cooperation
in investigating and dealing with the Hamanaka affair from
relevant authorities on a world-wide basis.
</P>
<P>
This cooperation is continuing, in particular with the
Securities and Futures Authority and the London Metal Exchange
regarding the finalization of investigations and involvement in
Hamanaka's activities of UK regulated firms and individuals, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
