<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Import 12 Million Tons of Cereals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, may 12 (xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) countries are expected to import 12
million tons of cereal this year to offset an increasing
shortage.
</P>
<P>
COMESA acting Secretary General Erastus Mwencha said here
Monday statistics show that output of wheat, maize, rice, millets
and sorghum have continued going down in the region, Zambia Daily
Mail reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The large import figure will no doubt have major implications
on the foreign exchange situation in our region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the potential areas under-utilized include irrigatable
land of 20 million hectares out of which 2.5 million hectares are
being currently irrigated, according to the national newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The region also has three major river basins -- the Nile,
Congo-Oubangui and the Zambezi -- which will boost irrigation.
</P>
<P>
"The potential in agriculture could be achieved if all COMESA
member countries are on the same wave length in terms of general
policy orientation and program implementation, " said Mwencha.
</P>
</TEXT>
