<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Revises U.S. Travel Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu has advanced his trip to Washington to meet with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright up to Wednesday from
Thursday, it was announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Albright invited Netanyahu for a meeting during their
telephone conversation Monday night and Netanyahu revised his
U.S. travel plans, advancing the departure time from Thursday to
early Wednesday morning, Netanyahu's office said.
</P>
<P>
The Washington meeting between Albright and Netanyahu will
intensify the diplomatic efforts for arranging
Israeli-Palestinian talks in Washington later this month under
President Bill Clinton's aegis and try to overcome the remaining
gaps between the Israeli and the U.S.-Palestinian positions on the
percentage of Israel's next troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
U.S. has proposed Israel to have a 13.1 percent troop
redeployment in the West Bank and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has accepted this proposal. Israel insisted that
it could only hand over 9 percent of the Wast Bank territories to
the PNA during the next redeployment.
</P>
<P>
But a deal was reportedly reached by Netanyahu and U.S. peace
envoy Denis Ross, who has just returned to Washington from Israel,
that Israel would hand over 9 percent now, and an additional 4
percent would be held "in escrow" by the United States, pending to
be handed over to the PNA on condition of their compliance of the
obligations including fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The planned Washington Israeli-Palestinian talks for Monday
were forced to be postponed to later this month, due to Israel's
rejection of U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
The frenzy of diplomatic activity that preceded the latest
Netanyahu-Albright conversation evidently upset National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon. He instructed his office to
issue a statement Monday night criticizing the manner in which the
current diplomatic contacts are being made behind the cabinet's
back.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Sharon views the attempt to develop
"creative ideas," a term used by Netanyahu, while casting "a fog"
over them at the international level as a "grave and worrisome
situation."
</P>
<P>
It charged that an attempt was being made to implement a 13
percent redeployment and contended that "hints to that effect
have been conveyed to the Americans."
</P>
<P>
Sharon was said to be holding the view that a withdrawal that
exceeded 9 percent threatens national security.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day visit in the United States, Netanyahu will
do the rounds of his supporters in the congress, make speeches
among American Jews and give several interviews to the
U.S. media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
