<HEADLINE> Mubarak to Visit France Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak will
start a three-day state visit to France on May 18 upon an
invitation from President Jacques Chirac, with Mideast peace
expected to top the agenda of their talks.
</P>
<P>
"The visit is particularly significant given the delicate
situation being experienced by the Mideast peace process which
arouses concern of all parties interested in the resumption of the
process," said Ali Maher, the Egyptian ambassador to Paris.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador was quoted Tuesday by local English daily the
Egyptian Gazette as hailing France's stance on the Mideast peace
process. Paris has been demanding the implementation by both sides
of the Oslo accords and relevant U.N. resolutions and supporting
the formation of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Maher expected that Mubarak and Chirac would discuss prospects
for a joint action to push forward and salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Several French ministers have visited Cairo over the past few
months to explore closer cooperation with the Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
Cairo and Paris are now studying preparations to celebrate the
200th anniversary of the establishment of Egyptian-French ties.
</P>
<P>
In 1798, the French Expedition led by Napoleon Bonaparte
invaded Egypt, marking the start of the bilateral relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
