<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene Mutations May Have Linkage with Hypertension: Studies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Mutations in a gene called
"angiotensin converting enzyme" (ACE) may be an important cause
for high blood pressure in men, but not in women, two separate
U.S. research teams reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A multicenter team led by Christopher J. O'Donnell of the
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston said that they found
consistent evidence in men but not in women of association and
genetic linkage of mutations in the ACE gene with diastolic blood
pressure (the second number in a blood pressure reading) and
association with hypertension.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, men with the variant gene had a 59 percent higher
risk of high blood pressure, said the report based on data drawn
from 3,095 men and women participating in the Framingham Heart
Study.
</P>
<P>
Another team led by Myriam Fornage of the University of Texas
at Houston Health Science Center reported some additional findings
that support a role for the ACE gene in blood pressure control.
</P>
<P>
Using data on 1,488 siblings with an average age of 15, the
investigators evaluated the contribution to blood pressure
variations of alterations in four gene regions, including the
region for ACE.
</P>
<P>
"In sex-specific analyses, genetic variation in the region of
the ACE gene significantly influenced individual blood pressure
variation in males...but not in females," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Eric Boerwinkle of the University of Texax, senior author of
the second report, said that ACE gene was a likely suspect for
high blood pressure because the enzyme that the gene encodes plays
a role in keeping the blood volume normal by controlling salt and
water balance.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the researchers now must analyze the gene region more
closely to map the exact address of the ACE gene -- and the genes
next to it -- to determine their exact functions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
