<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Equally Important: Lithuanian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Lithuania attaches equal
importance to relations with the United States and Russia,
Lithuanian President Valdas Adamkus said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Moscow News, Adamkus said Lithuania
is a European country and intends "to coordinate" its moves
officially with other European nations.
</P>
<P>
He said he does not want to "put any special stress on
relations with the U.S.," Adamkus said. "Washington will be given
as much attention as our eastern neighbor, democratic Russia."
</P>
<P>
When answering a question why Lithuania rejected the security
guarantees proposed by Russia last autumn and gave preference to
membership in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO),
Adamkus said Russia's proposals were "declarative" and that it was
unclear how they could be ultimately implemented.
</P>
<P>
NATO is proposing a radically different concept. "It's a
process in which all European nations are involved, which
guarantees security in the whole Europe," he said, adding that the
position on ethnic minorities in Lithuania differs from those in
Latvia and even Estonia.
</P>
<P>
Adamkus said he stands for diplomatic moves and mutually
acceptable terms in settling problems existing between Russia and
Latvia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
