<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Downplays Unofficial Count </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos on
Tuesday advised all the leading presidential candidates not to
bank too much on the initial results of the unofficial counting of
the ballots in Monday's elections.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here, Ramos said the people should
wait for the official announcement from the Commission on
Elections (Comelec) and the quick count conducted by the National
Movement for Free Elections (Namfrel).
</P>
<P>
Namfrel is the only duly-accredited citizen arm of the Comelec,
the government agency overseeing elections, to conduct the
unofficial quick counting of the votes cast for the president.
</P>
<P>
But several other groups including a private radio station DZRH
and a local television station ABS-CBN also conducted unofficial
counting of the votes.
</P>
<P>
According to partial results issued by these groups including
Namfrel as of Tuesday noon, Vice President Joseph Estrada of the
main opposition LAMMP (Fight of Patriotic Filipino Masses) has
held a massive early lead among the 10 official presidential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
The results also showed that Speaker of the House of
Representatives Jose de Venecia, picked by Ramos as the
presidential bet of the ruling party, lagged far behind Estrada.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos, who is to step down on June 30 when his
constitutionally-mandated six-year term ends, called on all the
presidential contenders to be cautious on the initial unofficial
count.
</P>
<P>
"The reports constitute only 1.5 percent of the actual vote,
assuming that there was a large turnout from 75 to 80 percent,"
Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
The Comelec earlier estimated that 80 percent of the 34 million
registered Filipino voters cast their votes in Monday's national
and local elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told reporters that he is still confident that his
preferred successor De Venecia will be the victor in the
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also commented on the upbeat mood in the stock market and
the strong performance of the peso in the foreign exchange market
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Ramos, the major reason for the stability of the
two markets was the conduct of honest, orderly and peaceful
elections Monday as well as the assurance of the presidential
candidates and parties that they will respect the will of the
people.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to Monday's elections, the local stock and
currency markets had been turbulent due to fears of a failure of
elections to be caused by election violence or massive cheating.
</P>
<P>
But on Monday, the voting was conducted in a relatively
peaceful way despite sporadic election-related violence incidents
during which at least 13 people were reportedly killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
