<HEADLINE> Philippine President Calls on Nation to Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Tuesday called on all the candidates, political parties and the
entire nation to unite in the heat of the electoral contest to
ensure the country's continued march to peace and development.
</P>
<P>
"I am calling on all of our people to unite after this very
intense and exciting election campaign," Ramos said in a briefing
at the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
"The voting is over, the counting has begun and it is the duty
of everyone to protect the sanctity of the ballot by making sure
that the vote cast by the voter is counted for the candidate that
he voted for," he said.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report from the Philippine National Police, Ramos
noted that a total of 151 election-related incidents were recorded
in 1998, compared to 97 incidents in the 1995 midterm polls.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the number of casualties is much less in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"As of the last report, 40 have been killed in various parts of
the country in 1998 -- which is a 45 percent decrease compared to
the 73 in 1995," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president attributed the lower number of casualties during
Monday's elections to the less use of deadly weapons and the
country's more efficient electoral system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
