<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Watchdog Group Warns of Cheating in Philippines' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A poll watchdog group in the
Philippines warned Tuesday that cheating could happen at the
municipal and provincial level within three days if it continues
to be denied of a copy of the election returns.
</P>
<P>
Jose Concepcion, chairman of the National Citizens Movement for
Free Elections (Namfrel), told reporters here that cheating could
be prevented if the sixth copy of the election returns is given to
Namfrel coordinators and volunteers, which they would use in
determining whether the votes for the candidates are identical.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, election returns are impressed in seven
copies. While Namfrel should be provided with the sixth copy, the
other copies are given to the Congress, the election commission,
and major political parties.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel is the only non-governmental organization authorized by
the Commission on Elections to conduct unofficial quick count
operations.
</P>
<P>
"It (sixth copy) is important in the precinct level because it
can be corrected," said Concepcion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Guillermo Luz, secretary general of Namfrel,
admitted the slowness in tabulating the initial results, but said
that this was due to the refusal of polling officers to provide
the sixth copy.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel said earlier that it could release the final unofficial
results within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The official vote counting has been going on at a very slow
pace since it began Monday afternoon after the poll closed. The
final results may not come out in two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of 34 million Filipino voters cast ballots
Monday, choosing a new president, a vice president, 12 out of 24
senators, 260 members of the House of Representatives and
thousands of local officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
