<HEADLINE> Jones Runs Best in World Fastest Women Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 12 (Xinhua) -- World champion Marion Jones of the
United States justified the world title by clocking her personal
best of 10.71 seconds to win the world fastest women race in the
100 meters sprint here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
By beating local heroine Li Xuemei, who shocked the world in
her personal best of 10.79 seconds last year, the American woman
sliced off 0.05 seconds of her previous personal best of 10.76
seconds set in the World Athletics Championships last year in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
Days ago in the IAAF Grand Prix in Japan, the 22-year-old Jones
timed 10.79 seconds, signalling her readiness and top-notched
calibre to clinch the title of the world fastest woman.
</P>
<P>
"The track seems pretty good, I can definitely lift my personal
best in this big race," said Jones in a pre-race press conference
yesterday, who arrived here Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuemei of Sichuan province, who broke both the women's 100
and 200 meters in the Chinese national games, finished in a
distant fourth place in 11.21 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"I was disappointed with my performance today, because I was
slow in the start which was the main reason for my defeat," Li
Xuemei said on the spot.
</P>
<P>
A pair of Bahamas women sprinters finished second and third,
with Savatheda Fynes in 11.06 seconds and Chandra Sturrup in 11.09
seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
