another 20.7 points to close at 1400.05 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the stock prices ended 1.5 percent lower in
subdued trading as foreign institutional investors remained wary
of investing in the region. They also noted that the STII had
suffered due to losses in Singapore Press Holdings and Keppel
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume was still thin at 117.46 million units,
worth 189.04 million Singapore dollars (about 115.97 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 270 to 57, while 267
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Guthrie was the most actively traded stock as it registered a
turnover of 12.66 million units. It was followed by TSM which had
11.72 million shares traded. Hong Kong Land was next with 6.41
million of its shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 60 cents to finish at 30.9 Singapore
dollars. ASEAN increased by 30 cents to end at seven U.S. dollars.
GP Battery was up by 22 cents to close at 4.26 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, GE Life was the biggest loser as it declined
by 50 cents to end at 11 Singapore dollars. DBS (Development Bank
of Singapore) Foreign and SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) fell by
30 cents each to close at 9.65 and 15.6 Singapore dollars
respectively. Perlis lost 28 cents to finish at 2.22 Singapore
dollars. 
