<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down on U.S. Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket closed
down marginally Tuesday on concern over U.S. interest rates and
the collapse of merger talks between two big funds managers.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp continued to lose ground on
negative sentiment towards its quarterly results after U.S.
investors sold their American Depository Receipts overnight.
</P>
<P>
But resources giant BHP gained ground in the afternoon session
on takeover rumors and bargain hunters, despite lower world
commodity prices overnight.
</P>
<P>
"There are rumors of a possible merger with Rio Tinto," said
senior broker Peter Struk of Reynolds &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
He also said the market was nervous on debate over a possible
rise in U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries closed down 10.7 points at 2786.9 after
trading between 2797.6 and 2772.3.
</P>
<P>
The all resources lost 1.3 points to 1181.3, and the all
industrials fell 21.8 to 4795.6.
</P>
<P>
Shares in both Lend Lease Corp and National Mutual Holdings
fell after announcing that a plan to build a funds management
powerhouse had broken down.
</P>
<P>
In October, both agreed to merge their funds assets into one
house managing 51 billion Australian dollars (33.15 billion U.S.
dollars), under a respective 51/49 split, to increase economies of
scale.
</P>
<P>
National Mutual dropped 27.7 cents, or 7.14 percent, while Lend
Lease slumped 4.34 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary shares in Rupert Murdoch's News Corp fell 36 cents to
9.96 Australian dollars while its preferred scrip slipped 14 to
8.86.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a thin 297.04 million valued at 854.60
million Australian dollars (555.49 million U.S. dollars). Falls
outnumbered rises 563 to 471, with 411 stocks steady.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank gained 8.5 cents, ANZ gained six,
Commonwealth dipped one and Westpac slipped 2.9 cents.
</P>
<P>
Topping volume was Telstra Corp with 16.78 million shares
traded at a value of 61.04 million Australian dollars (about 39
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
BHP shares traded strongly after noon to close up five cents on
a turnover of 2.93 million Australian dollars (about 1.9 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed down 3.3 points at 1321.3, with Normandy
Mining losing three cents and Lihir Gold losing two. Sydney
trading in gold bullion closed at 299.80 U.S. dollars an ounce,
down 0.45. 
