<HEADLINE> Iraqi Vice PM Calls on France to Resume Diplomatic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice Prime Minister Tarik Aziz
Tuesday called on France to resume diplomatic relations with Iraq,
which were cut by Baghdad seven years ago for France's
participation in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who is on a five-day visit in France from Monday, said
during a meeting with the president of French Senate, Rene Monory,
that there is no bilateral dispute between Iraq and France.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the government and public opinion of France
support Iraq. We appreciate the attitude of France and the efforts
it has deployed over the past few years. But we want more
intensive activities in this direction, more understanding and
more support from our French friends," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.N. sanctions against Iraq has lasted too
long and it has brought tragic consequences to the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
On the cooperation between Iraq and the United Nations special
commission of arms inspection (UNSCOM), Aziz said he was "above
all satisfied" with it although both sides have to face up to
many difficulties in their relations.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Aziz will be received by President Jacques
Chirac, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
He is also scheduled to meet with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan, who is on a visit here, on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
