<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Leader Offers Surrender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The leader of Sierra Leone's former
military junta has been confirmed to be on the way to surrender,
according to a statement from the west African peace keeping
force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued in the Sierra Leonean capital Freetown
Monday, said the ECOMOG High Command was aware of the attempt of
Johnny Paul Koroma, the fleeing junta leader, to surrender to the
Catholic mission in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, Koroma has offered surrender to
the Catholic Dioceses headed by Bishop George Biguzzi in Makeni,
northern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
He did not want to surrender to ECOMOG for fear of his life
and that of his family.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG said the sub-regional force would encourage the former
junta leader and his followers to surrender to ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, ECOMOG was not interested in dead
bodies, which is seen as indication that Koroma and his men would
not be killed if they gave themselves up to the force.
</P>
<P>
Koroma, who seized power from the elected government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah last May, was dislodged in
mid-February by the Nigerian-led ECOMOG forces.
</P>
<P>
While he ran out of the net of the sub-regional force,
remnants of his army, along with the Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) rebels, have since been waging war against the advancing
ECOMOG in the eastern and northern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
After nearly two weeks' heavy fighting, ECOMOG has seized the
town of Koidu in the east border with Guinea when it announced
Monday the killing of some 150 Koroma loyalists and RUF rebels,
as well as the capture of 30 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
