<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shipping Lines's New Levy in Port Mombasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 12 (Xinhua) -- International shipping lines have
introduced a 70 U.S. Dollars per container congestion surcharge
for all cargoes shipped in and out of the port of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
The International Organization of Vessel Sharing Agreement
(IOVSA) members trading among South Africa, East Africa, Middle
East and Pakistan last week issued a notice, saying that the
surcharge was imposed because of major delays in berthing,
discharge and loading of containers at the port.
</P>
<P>
"Shippers are aware that major delays have occurred at the
port since the end of December 1997 and in the foreseeable future
such berthing delays are expected to continue," the Kenya Daily
Nation newspaper Tuesday quoted the notice as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Ports Authority (KPA) held an emergent meeting last
week with shipping lines under the East African Conference Lines
(EACL) to avert the introduction of the levy, said the report.
</P>
<P>
By last week, more than 12 vessels were waiting to discharge
their cargo and some of the waiting vessels which arrived as
early as last month were still anchored mid-stream due to lack of
berthing space.
</P>
<P>
Shipping lines complained that the congestion at Port Mombasa
was so severe that ships were delayed to up to between five and
eight days before they got berthing space.
</P>
<P>
KPA Managing Director Lenny Mwangola in a statement attributed
the ship congestions at the port to the collapse of roads and
railways network in the east African country caused by El Nino
rains.
</P>
<P>
He said that heavy rains during the past several months had
slowed the off-take of cargo from the port due to constraints in
the rail and road transport system.
</P>
<P>
In order to regain a fluid situation and movement of cargo, he
said, KPA will facilitate the removal of hundreds of
containerized imports which had over-stayed at the port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
