<HEADLINE> Malaysia Bars Foreign Equity in Local TV Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will not allow
foreign stakes in local television stations although foreigners
have sought for such equity holding, it was announced here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat said this had been decided
as there is no national policy providing for "equity participation
by foreign entities or individuals in terrestrial stations."
</P>
<P>
The minister said at a press conference here that he was aware
that foreigners were keen in owning equity stakes in local
broadcasting companies.
</P>
<P>
"But before we strayed, let me reiterate that the country's
television stations are for local equity participation only," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed speculation that the operator of the Johor-based
Best 104 radio station had been granted permission to also run a
television network.
</P>
<P>
"Best 104 has only been given a radio broadcasting license.
Even if they apply to start a television station, they will not
get the approval as the government will no longer issue new
licenses for television stations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has now six television networks, including the two run
by government-owned Radio and Television Malaysia (RTM). The rest
are TV3, Metrovison, NTV7 and the recently licensed Langkawi-based
IMT-GT which covers the Indonesia, Thailand and Malaysia growth
triangle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
