<HEADLINE> Seoul Warns Against Septicemia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government Tuesday
issued a warning for the whole country against septicemia as its
vibrio has been found in fish and clams caught in western and
southern coasts of South Cholla Province.
</P>
<P>
The disease is reportedly caused by eating raw fish and
shellfish carrying septicemia bacilli and its virus can be lethal
to human beings.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health and Welfare particularly cautioned
those who have liver problems not to eat raw fish, clams and
other seafood.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also warned that fishermen could be infected with
the virus through cuts or other wounds suffered during their work.
</P>
<P>
Septicemia is an epidemic in the coastal areas of the nation in
June-October every year.
</P>
<P>
This year's high temperatures have been blamed for having
brought the the disease 20 days earlier than previous years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics of the ministry showed that South Korea had 23
septicemia patients last year, of whom 11 people had died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
