<HEADLINE> Australia's New Election Could Be Imminent: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard Tuesday
warned his colleagues to prepare themselves for an election that
could be called within weeks as his treasurer prepared to hand
down a budget that could well decide the outcome of the poll.
</P>
<P>
However, Howard told the coalition party meeting that he had
not yet made up his mind when the election would be called, but
ruled out a poll before the end of the current budget session of
parliament, which is due to run until July 2, the Australian
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Howard made clear the government would be going to the polls on
its economic record, which will be confirmed Tuesday night with
the first budget surplus for eight years.
</P>
<P>
"I am very proud to say that the economy of Australia is the
strongest it has been for a quarter of a century," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were backed up by Treasurer Peter Costello in his
final remarks before handing down the statement.
</P>
<P>
Costello said the statement would "put our house right" and
"get the economic fundamentals right" to create opportunities for
future Australians.
</P>
<P>
However, he moved to play down expectations with a reference to
the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"If it hadn't been for the Asian crisis Australian growth would
have been stronger. That's the fact," Costello said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
