<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Free Asia Pacific Show Held in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Tax Free Asia Pacific (TFAP)'98
was kicked off here Tuesday with a total of 260 exhibitors from
more than 20 countries and regions displaying a wide range of duty
and tax free products.
</P>
<P>
Organized by Tax Free World Association (TFWA), the event is
being held in Hong Kong for the first time, in recognition of its
premier status in duty free sales in the Asia Pacific region,
Jacky Paquet, president of TFWA, said at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Sales of tax free products in Hong Kong amounted to 830 million
U.S. dollars in 1996 while the Kai Tak Airport, with sales of 380
million U.S. dollars, beat all the other rivals to be the region's
No. 1 retail outlet, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over 350 brands covering all categories -- liquor, tobacco,
fragrances and cosmetics, accessories, jewelry, gifts and
confectionery are displayed at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center through Friday to an anticipated 3,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the exhibition, a conference was held Monday,
reviewing the events and changes in the duty free industry over
the past year and assessing the effects of the Asian financial
crisis on the industry.
</P>
<P>
TFAP was started in 1995 in Singapore in light of Asia's ever
growing duty free market. In 1996, Asia's sales of duty free
products reached 6.4 billion U.S. dollars, representing 30.7
percent of the industry's worldwide sales, according to TFWA
figures.
</P>
<P>
TFWA was created in 1984, whose members represent up to 90
percent of the global tax free industry. It organizes Tax Free
World Exhibition in Cannes, France, every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
