<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Protection of Intellectual Property Rights Improved: US Scholar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 12 (Xinhua) -- There has been definite
improvement in the protection of intellectual property in China in
recent years, Thomas Moga, an American legal specialist in
copyrights, patents and trademarks, said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Moga, who has had extensive consultancy and teaching experience
in China's mainland and Taiwan on intellectual property
protection, said that the U.S. companies should not lose the
opportunities for entering the Chinese market due to their
concerns over the intellectual property protection situation in
China.
</P>
<P>
Moga made the remarks when he met with foreign and local
journalists as well as correspondents from China's mainland and
Macao at the American Consulate General in Hong Kong on his way
from the United States to Shenyang, a city in northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
However, Moga reminded the U.S. companies that intend to enter
the Chinese market to register their trademarks in China first in
a effort to protect their copyrights.
</P>
<P>
Many American companies are not aware of the present Customs
situation in China, Moga said, adding the foreign owners of the
intellectual property rights should pre-register their rights in
the Chinese Customs offices.
</P>
<P>
There are laws in China which people can use to protect
themselves, Moga said. For example, the Consumers Rights Law will
protect the rights of the consumers.
</P>
<P>
"If you find the quality of what you have bought are not
satisfactory, you can take it back to the supplier and get your
money back, and there will be penalty for the sellers," Moga said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
