<HEADLINE> BMW Won't Raise Offer for Rolls-Royce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- German auto maker BMW AG reaffirmed
on Tuesday that it will not raise its offer for British luxury
car manufacturer Rolls-Royce despite a much higher counter bid
by its German rival, Volkswagen AG.
</P>
<P>
"Under no circumstances will BMW withdraw or change its current
offer," BMW chief Bernd Pischetsrieder told a shareholders
assembly in Munich.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the battle over Rolls-Royce was not over yet,
Pischetsrieder also noted that only BMW now had an agreement with
British engine maker Rolls-Royce PLC on the exclusive right to the
name of Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
Pischetsrieder's remarks came after the bidding war for the
noble British brand took a surprise turn last Thursday after
Vickers, the parent firm of Rolls-Royce Motor Cars, turned to
support Volkswagen to take over the car-maker.
</P>
<P>
The about-face was due to an improved bid from Volkswagen,
which was about 430 million pounds (713.2 million U.S. dollars),
well above the 340 million pounds (564 million dollars) offered by
BMW.
</P>
<P>
BMW had previously engaged in exclusive talks with Vickers on
the planned takeover. But the British company argued that the
higher offer made by Volkswagen would bring more benefits to its
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
A decision is due to be made by a special shareholders meeting
of the British company on June 4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
