<HEADLINE> Sharif Says ECO States Recognize Pakistan's Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Tuesday that all leaders of the Economic Cooperation
Organization (ECO) have recognized the importance of Pakistan in
promoting regional cooperation in economic development.
</P>
<P>
"All ECO leaders were unanimous in recognizing Pakistan's
active role in promoting regional cooperation in all areas of
economic development," Sharif said in a statement upon arrival
back after attending the ECO Summit meeting in Almaty, capital of
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
He said the ECO summit particularly focused on ways to enhance
cooperation in the fields of transport, communications, trade,
investment and rapid development of gas and oil resources.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said the most noteworthy outcome of the summit was the
signing of a regional Transit Trade Framework Agreement which
recognized Pakistan as the only vital link between Central Asia
and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to accelerating the implementation of ECO's
transport and communications plans linking the member states with
each other and the outside world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that during his stay in Almaty he also talked with
other ECO leaders in a bid to obtain endorsement for the holding
of the proposed Central Asia-South Asia economic summit in
Pakistan in September this year in collaboration with the World
Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
He described the summit as an "important meeting" which served
to reaffirm the collective commitment of ECO member states to
promoting regional cooperation for the socio-economic development
and well-being of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
