<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Grants Humanitarian Aid to Southern Caucasus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the 15-nation European Union (EU), cleared on
Tuesday humanitarian aid worth 9.66 million ECU (10.56 million
U.S. dollars) for southern Caucasus countries.
</P>
<P>
The aid will be provided to Armenia (1.6 million ECU),
Azerbaijan (4.1 million ECU) and Georgia (3.96 million ECU).
</P>
<P>
The aid, to be managed by the European Community Humanitarian
Office, will enable non-government organizations to carry out
assistance programs in the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The grant was made in response to a United Nations appeal on
behalf of the region which is experiencing a slight economic
upturn after extreme hardships in the wake of independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The aid is also expected to complement resources made available
by other European Commission services, and bilateral aid from EU
member states, as well as funding from the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund, commission officials said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of people have been displaced and
humanitarian aid is essential to ensure the survival of the most
vulnerable in the southern Caucasus region. Their situation
results from conflicts in Abkhazia, Ossetia and Nagorny-Karabakh
where peace talks are underway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The European Investment Bank will grant a loan of 43
million ECU (about 46.5 million U.S. dollars) to upgrade and
expand the potash manufacturing capacity in the southeastern part
of the Dead Sea.
</P>
<P>
Semi-official Jordan Times Monday quoted a statement by a
visiting European Commission delegation as saying that the loan,
which is part of the EIB's continuing efforts in support of the
industrial sector in the Middle East, will be made available to
the Arab Potash Company (APC), the world's fifth largest potash
producer.
</P>
<P>
The loan will fund the expansion of APC's existing solar
evaporation surface area, salt ponds as well as the installation
of a new brine pumping station.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Swiss government has decided to grant Jordan 1.2
million Swiss francs (800,000 dollars) to help fund the hotel
personnel training programs undertaken by the Ministry of Tourism,
according to Tourism Minister Aqel Beltaji.
</P>
<P>
The advanced training programs are bound to help Jordan's
hotel staff offer visitors high-quality services, he said.
</P>
<P>
Swiss experts asserted in a study earlier conducted in the
kingdom that Jordan is in need of thousands of trained hotel
personnel, as the number of hotels is steadily rising, he added.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The World Bank Monday approved to provide a credit of
4.2 million U.S. dollars to help Turkey develop five commodity
exchange markets, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency said that the credit will be used to improve
the infrastructure of the commodity exchange markets in the
provinces of Eskisehir, Edirne, Izmir, Polatli and Sanliurfa.
</P>
<P>
Halil Sariarslan, official from the Turkish Union of Chambers
and Commodity Exchanges was quoted as saying that the firms, which
will set up the infrastructure of the commodity exchanges, will be
paid directly by using this credit.
</P>
<P>
Sariarslan said that the five commodity exchanges will make
an investment worth 1.2 million dollars within the same project,
adding that the project will be coordinated by Turkey's Ministry
of Industry and Trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
