<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Withdrawal of Financial Support for Mozambican </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) has no
intention to withdraw its financial support for the local
elections scheduled on June 30 in Mozambique, one European
Commission official has said.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the office of the European Commission in Mozambique
Neves Da Silva said here Monday that the European Union and the
United Nations Development Program have worked out a
20-million-U.S.-Dollar plan to support the Mozambican government
with the local elections.
</P>
<P>
"Technically speaking, the National Electoral Commission (CNE)
of Mozambique, the Technical Secretariat of Election
Administration (STAE) and other government organs have done
excellent work. The preparatory plans have been carried out
quickly and in time. I am satisfied," the Noticias newspaper
Tuesday quoted Silva as saying.
</P>
<P>
Silva, the EU representative to Mozambique and the ambassadors
from some western countries held discussions with Mozambican
Minister of State Administration Alfredo Gamito last Wednesday,
agreeing that various plans for the elections have been
implemented.
</P>
<P>
Silva disclosed that Mozambican government has signed
contracts with the suppliers of the materials to be used in the
elections, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
He added that EU formally assured the suppliers that the
problems had been resolved. But he did not give the details.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, the weekly Domingo quoted a diplomat based in
Maputo as saying that EU would withdraw its financial support for
Mozambique because the ruling Mozambique Liberation Front Party
(FRELIMO) and the biggest opposition party Mozambican National
Resistance (RENAMO) and other opposition parties were unable to
reach accommodation on the issue of local elections, especially
on the redefinition of the roles of the CNE and the STAE.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties insisted that their members be admitted
into the STAE while FRELIMO refused their demand on the ground
that the STAE is a government organ and cannot be politicized.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government said Monday that it had not received
any information about EU withdrawing its support for the
elections in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Gamito said that all the goals of various plans have been
achieved and the next step is to order the materials necessary in
the elections.
</P>
<P>
RENAMO and some other opposition parties previously refused to
participate in the local elections to be held in June in the 33
cities and towns on the excuse that there was rigging in the
voters registration in the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
But FRELIMO said that it would participate in the elections
scheduled to be held in June even if all other parties boycotted
the polls.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the international community would impose
pressure on the rivaling parties so that they will make mutual
concessions to guarantee the smooth going of the elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
