<HEADLINE> Remains of "Salt Man" to Be Put on Display </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Cultural Heritage
Organization announced on Tuesday that the remains of a "salt
man" of 2,000 years ago and his belongings discovered in 1993 will
be put on display in an exhibition as of May 18.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, the exhibition is
to be held at Iran's National Museum downtown Tehran on the
occasion of the Cultural Heritage Day.
</P>
<P>
The man's trunk, a boot still intact on his foot, several
pieces of bones, as well as several earthenware objects and metal
tools will be put on display at the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
The half body and a leg of the man, known later as "salt man,"
along with some of his belongings were found during excavations at
a salt mine in Hamzehlou village of Zanjan province, about 300
kilometers west to the capital Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The remains were believed to belong to a 40-year old hunter or
a prince who had been wounded for yet unknown reasons, a short
while before his death, IRNA added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Commend Outstanding Teachers, Students in Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- China will commend 10 outstanding
teachers working under the Spring Bud Project, a project aiming to
help girls with their education, and 10 excellent girl students
aided by the project before June 1, the International Children's
Day.
</P>
<P>
Also commended will be groups and individuals making special
contribution to the project. The event, second of its kind, is
organized by the China Children and Youth Fund and All-China
Women's Federation (ACWF).
</P>
<P>
For the 10 best girl students, the Fund will pay for their
education until college graduation if their academic performance
is good enough to last their schooling to university campuses,
according to a circular for the commendation issued by the ACWF
recently.
</P>
<P>
Another non-government project to help school-age children in
poverty-stricken areas to have access to proper education after
the much publicized Hope Project, the Spring Bud Project was
launched in 1989 and has since helped some 600,000 girls return to
school.
</P>
<P>
Improvement of children's health and education in rural areas,
especially in poor areas, remains China's main task in
guaranteeing children's welfare, said Liu Hairong, a ACWF vice
chairperson.
</P>
<P>
Sharp imbalances have been recorded in the conditions of urban
and rural children, with the mortality of rural infants and
children below the age of five twice that of their urban siblings,
and the incidence of severe malnutrition being 4.6 percent for
urban children below five and 19.5 percent for rural ones.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Spring Bud Project commendation, there will be
10 other major events held in Beijing around June 1 in a move to
arouse deeper awareness of the children's welfare among the
citizens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Bridge Linking Somali Capital Cut off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 12 (Xinhua)-- The important bridge that linked
Mogadishu to Kismaio has been cut off by the Majerten forces led
by General Mohamed Saeed Jirsi Morgan Monday, reports from the
southern Somali region of Lower Jubba indicated.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses told Xinhua in Mogadishu via VHF radio that
General Morgan's men attached several mines and large explosives
in many parts of the bridge and its underneath then exploded it
on a remote control device.
</P>
<P>
People in the area were terrified by the loud noise from the
bridge which has now fallen for the second time since the
fighting began in mid April.
</P>
<P>
Morgan's militiamen are now in defensive positions behind the
wreckage of Kamsuma bridge, 90 km north of Kismaio.
</P>
<P>
The destruction of the bridge followed a bitter fighting
between the Marehan militiamen and those of the Majerten forces
over the control of the port town.
</P>
<P>
Even though there are many other ways to reach the port town
of Kismaio, still Kamsuma bridge has been the most important road
since it is the only tarmac street linking Mogadishu and Kismaio.
</P>
<P>
According to the Marehan SNF militia commanders, the reason
for blowing off the bridge is due to the weak militia strength of
Morgan's who ultimately decided to destroy the bridge as the best
and cheapest defense against the Marehans.
</P>
<P>
The Kamsuma bridge has been beneficial economically for the
two southern regions of Lower Juba and Middle Juba for its smooth
facilitation of all commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
With the bridge now destroyed, thousands of people are moving
to neighboring towns and villages to avoid further fighting and
possible spread of famine.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 200 people are believed to have died in the
conflict over the control of Kismaio in Lower Jubba region and
more than 300 others were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Baidoa national reconciliation conference
scheduled on April 15 is obviously not taking place in time.
</P>
<P>
Abdulkadir Mohamed Aden Zoppe, a prominent leader of the
Rahanwein community, told the reporters Tuesday that despite the
financial difficulties, the conference won't start as long as
Hussein Aidid's militiamen remain in the regions of Bau and
Bakol.
</P>
<P>
According to Zoppe, Hussein Aidid has agreed with the
Rahanweins to pull out from Baidoa in a systematic way so as to
avoid the free-lance gangs who would benefit from the power
vacuum in those regions after their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the on-going peace meeting for the faction
leaders in the capital is expected to announce the postponement
of the Baidoa conference by Thursday for another 45 days or more
for the third time since the Cairo peace deal was signed late
last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Export to Japan Up nearly 21 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria registered a 20.8-percent
increase in its export to Japan last year with a total value of
201.1 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Japan External Trade Organization (JETRO)
reaching here Tuesday said crude oil accounts for 91.9 percent of
the total export from Nigeria to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Quoting statistics`from the Japan Tariff Association, the
statement said Nigeria exported 184.9 million Dollars worth of
crude oil to Japan in 1997, a growth of 16.6 percent from the
previous year's 158.5 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, non-oil export from Nigeria to Japan stood at 16
million Dollars. These products could be broken down into sesame
seed, leather, cotton, cocoa beans and live animals.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Nigeria's total import from Japan reached 214.6
million Dollars, a decrease of 30.8 percent from 1996's 310
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Major imported goods include iron and steel, motor buses,
trucks, passenger motorcars, engines and electrical machinery,
motorcycles, engine parts, new tyres, pumps, chemicals,
photographic films, audio visuals and constructing, mining or
lifting machinery.
</P>
<P>
JETRO said trade between the two countries was encouraging and
would continue to be strengthened further in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
