<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Rejects New Round of Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will reject any call
for the World Trade Organization (WTO) meeting in Geneva next
week to hold a fresh round of trade talks to re-discuss all
aspects of multilateral trade, International Trade and Industry
Minister Rafidah Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's stand is that the resolutions endorsed in the
earlier Uruguay Round should be settled first before a fresh round
of talks could start, Rafidah said after attending the summit
meeting of the Group of 15 (G-15) developing countries in Cairo
Monday, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"As for Malaysia the issue before us is the question of
economic recovery. We don't have the time to concentrate on
discussing again matters relating to a new round of multilateral
trade talks given the limited time," Rafidah was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
She said that despite pressures from developed countries,
Malaysia adamantly maintained that opening the market for specific
sectors could be expedited through sectoral liberalization.
</P>
<P>
"It should not be through what is called as multilateral as in
a global or comprehensive context encompassing all items and all
matters," Rafidah said, adding that Malaysia, as a developing
country, could not afford to do so at the moment because it had to
handle several other problems.
</P>
<P>
Several countries at a meeting of G-15 trade ministers prior to
the summit supported Malaysia's stand, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Several countries share the same stand as Malaysia's on the
WTO. They accept the recommendations of the trade ministers'
meeting where Malaysia itself distributed the policy paper on the
stand of the developing countries in the WTO for next week's WTO
meeting," Rafidah said.
</P>
<P>
In the policy paper, Malaysia suggested, among other things,
that new issues relating to the WTO should require no scrutiny and
that whatever has been agreed to in the past should be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever the agenda before us, that's all that we'll have to
implement. The rest is just for information. For example if we
want to discuss government procurement or another issue, it is
only for information. It should not be discussed in the WTO as a
trade issue," she said.
</P>
<P>
During the G-15 summit's first day deliberations, she said,
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad submitted a working paper on the
Asian financial crisis detailing out the negative impact of
currency devaluation and the resultant social and economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
She expected the G-15 leaders to reach certain agreement to
jointly tackle currency-trading problems with other organizations.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
