<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Backs a Permanent Criminal Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union decided Tuesday
to back the establishment of a permanent international criminal
court (ICC).
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union set aside a grant of 390,000 European
Currency Unions (435,000 U.S. dollars) for the 1998 international
campaign to set up the ICC court.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be awarded to the non-government organization,
"No Peace Without Justice" (NGO), which has been fighting for the
adoption of an international treaty on the ICC court by the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Societies shattered by the nightmare of war cannot resume
normality unless the guilty are brought to justice. We have seen
this in Yugoslavia, in Rwanda and in other places," European
Commissioner Hans van den Broek said.
</P>
<P>
A grant of 238,330 ECUs (265,880 dollars) will also be
earmarked by the body to help the work of the International
Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia in the Hague with a
specialized library, a technical support system and a study place
for tribunal staff.
</P>
<P>
An international criminal court treaty conference is scheduled
for June and July this year when non-government organizations are
expected to campaign with conferences, advocacy and participation
in Rome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
