<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Tapes 10.71 in World Fastest Women Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, China, May 12 (Xinhua) -- American world champion
Marion Jones bolted off from the blockers like a thunder out of
the blue, leading all the way to win the eye-popping world fastest
women race with a fabulous time of 10.71 seconds here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old former basketball star beat off all her
opponents in the 100 meters with a sizable edge, improving her
personal best by 0.05 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Her impressive winning time is the fastest time in 10 years,
and only her compatriot Florence Griffith-Joyner registered faster
clockings in history.
</P>
<P>
Savatheda Fynes of Bahamas, world bronze medalist, romped home
in 11.06, ahead of her compatriot Chandra Sturrup who finished
third in 11.09. The pair also improved their personal bests.
</P>
<P>
China's Li Xuemei, who was regarded as a tough nut to crack for
Jones before the big duel, disappointed her hometown crowd greatly
by wrapping up fourth in 11.21, well out of her personal best of
10.79.
</P>
<P>
"I think I can run much faster than this, I am still in my
early career, I hope I can become a versatile athlete like Jackie
Joyner-Kersee. My goal is to win five gold medals in the Sydney
Olympics, I think it is very possible," said the multi-talented
American who is not only the world number one in the 100 and 200
meters, but also set a year's long jump best last week and did
pretty good in the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
While Jones celebrated her triumph with a big smile, her
nemesis Li Xuemei was seating in front of some 250 journalists at
the press conference with tears in her eyes. The 21-year-old burst
into tears when she answered questions.
</P>
<P>
"I am sorry I have disappointed all the home crowd and those
who have concern to me. I let them down. I want to say I am
terribly sorry. I don't know why I ran so slowly."
</P>
<P>
However, Lou Dapeng, an executive member of the International
Amateur Athletics Federation and president of the Chinese
Athletics Association, is the Mr. know-how. He pointed out that
lacking experience at international meets is the main reason to
explain Li's failure today.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese athletes only focus on their training, seldom go to
compete in the world, so they often fail to bring out their best
marks and feel nervous in the major competitions," said Lou.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 yelling home fans cheered for the
unprecedented event in history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
