<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy to Grow, But No Boost to Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economic growth is set to
pick up steam in the next two years, but this will still be
insufficient to stem the country's record-high unemployment, six
leading German economic research institutes predicted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The general economic conditions as well as the overwhelmingly
positive estimates shared by enterprises all speak in favor of a
continuing and even a strengthening economic upswing," said a
joint spring economic report issued by the six institutes
comprising the government's Council of Economic Advisors.
</P>
<P>
The report says Germany's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is
expected to grow by 2.6 percent this year and 2.7 percent in 1999,
after rising 2.2 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The main driving force for the economic recovery would continue
to be exports, which were expected to increase 10 percent this
year but slow to a growth of seven percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
After near stagnation in 1997, domestic demand was expected to
revive this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However the institutes also cautioned that despite the economic
upturn, the outlook on the job market would remain bleak. A
post-war record jobless rate of 11.5 percent was registered in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate is expected to remain virtually unchanged
this year and only fall to 11.0 percent next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
