<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- India conducted three underground nuclear tests at a site in
the country's northwestern desert, nearly 24 years after its only
other nuclear test. The move appeared to signal India's
determination to abandon decades of ambiguity in favor of openly
declaring it has nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton ordered Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright to meet Wednesday in Washington with Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu to try to resolve the latest impasse in the
Mideast peace talks. The United States has given Israel a deadline
for accepting a plan to withdraw from 13 percent of the West Bank,
but the deadline was extended when the prime minister refused.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Attorney General Janet Reno Monday requested the appointment
of an independent counsel to investigate allegations that Labor
Secretary Alexis M. Herman took part in an influence-peddling
scheme while she served as a White House aide during President
Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
-- The Immigration and Naturalization Service Monday stopped
issuing new visas for temporary ligh-tech workers, saying it
already has reached the category's annual limit. The move injected
new urgency into congressional efforts to raise the cap.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Inspections of older 737s continued after weekend
examinations showed extensive wear around wiring bundles near fuel
tanks in nearly half the 71 jets checked so far, the FAA said.
Airlines said inspections are moving quickly and any disruption of
travel has been minimal.
</P>
<P>
-- Clinton is to travel to Germany and meet with Chancellor
Kohl Wednesday. The visit is to commemorate the 50th anniversary
of the Berlin Airlift, but it is also expected to bolster Kohl's
bid for re-election. He faces a tough race against a strong Social
Democrat rival in the fall. 
</P>
