<HEADLINE> Japan Expresses Strong Regrets Over India's Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government expressed
regrets Tuesday over nuclear tests conducted by India Monday, and
urged the Indian government to halt its development of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely regrettable that India conducted such tests,
resisting the global trend to ban nuclear testing, while the
international community, including Japan, has repeatedly requested
India's new administration for to show maximum self-restraint on
nuclear policies," Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Kanezo Muraoka
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Japan strongly urges the Indian government to stop its
development of nuclear weapons immediately. Furthermore, Japan
calls on the other countries in the region to exercise
self-restraint in order to prevent the Indian nuclear testing from
harming the stability of the region,'' the top government
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Hiroshima Mayor Takashi Hiraoka said the Indian
nuclear tests were "extremely deplorable" because they came at the
same time as an exhibition on nuclear destruction in Hiroshima and
Nagasaki, which were hit by atomic bombs at the end of World War
II, was on shown in New Delhi, until May 15.
</P>
<P>
Nagasaki Mayor Itcho Ito also blasted India for conducting the
tests. He said he would lodge a "strong protest" with the Indian
government.
</P>
<P>
India conducted three underground nuclear tests in the western
desert state of Rajasthan on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
