<HEADLINE> Pittsburgh Welcomes Chinese Investment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Tom Murphy, mayor of the U.S. city
of Pittsburgh, invited investment from Chinese businesses in his
visit here today.
</P>
<P>
Murphy promised favorable policies and services to Chinese
investors. These preferential policies include low-interest loans
and financing supplied by Pittsburgh banks and the city
government, as well as assistance to limit investment risks, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The city will also provide such free services as airport
pick-up and basic office facilities, and help investors to
establish contacts in the local business community, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
Pittsburgh has also established an institute called the China
Trade Office to assist Chinese and U.S. businesses seeking
investment opportunities in each other's countries.
</P>
<P>
The institute makes Pittsburgh the first U.S. city to have an
office to promote and help investment from China, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Chinese media, he said that his city,
with a population of 2.5 million people, has advanced technologies
in the information industry, environmental protection and medical
research, the sectors that China needs to develop.
</P>
<P>
Murphy expressed his hope that Chinese businesses would
cooperate with Pittsburgh in these fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pittsburgh Welcomes Chinese Investment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some Chinese businesses have shown an interest in investing in
Pittsburgh and have contacted the city government, Murphy
said. Although there has been no progress so far, the mayor said
he is confident in the future of Chinese investment in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
Pittsburgh is known as the "Steel City" in the state of
Pennsylvania. Since 1994, it has attracted investment valued at
850 million U.S. dollars, and 150 foreign businesses have set up
plants in the city. A total of 29 institutes of high learning and
more than 100 high-tech companies are located in the city.
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies began investing in the United States at the
end of the 1970s. By last year, 526 Chinese trading or non-trading
businesses had been set up in the United States with contractual
investment of 682 million U.S. dollars, including 471 million
U.S. dollars from Chinese investors.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese investments cover such business sectors as
agriculture, technology, clothing and insurance.
</P>
<P>
A senior Chinese official in charge of Sino-U.S. trade said
that, although China is not a country of capital export, its
government encourages its businesses to invest abroad in resource
development and processing trade.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the United States, the world's most developed
country, Chinese companies can engage in labor-intensive
businesses, or manufacture products with a traditional competitive
edge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
