<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Have First Budget Surplus in 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Treasurer Peter
Costello Tuesday delivered the nation's budget for the financial
year of 1998-1999 with a surplus of 1.7 billion U.S. dollars, the
first in eight years.
</P>
<P>
Costello said the budget was designed to share out the benefits
of the past two years of cuts which helped overturn a 6 billion
U.S. dollar deficit the present coalition government inherited
from the previous administration, when it came to power in early
1996.
</P>
<P>
"We have achieved our goal (to have an economy in black within
the government's first three-year term of office)," the treasurer
told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-1999 financial year starts on July 1, 1998 and ends on
June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
In his third and final budget before an election, the treasurer
announced a range of new spending measures which focus on health
and the elderly, including greater access for self-funded retirees
to government concessions.
</P>
<P>
However, the budget indicated that the Asian financial crisis
would start to hit the Australian economy within the next 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth is forecast to slow down to 3 percent from 3.75
percent this year, unemployment is forecast to drop only
marginally to 7.75 percent by June 1999 from 7.9 percent last
month, and inflation is projected to rise to 2.5 percent next year
from the current 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Australia's current account deficit is projected to worsen to
19.5 billion U.S. dollars during the next financial year, or 5.25
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP), due to the Asian
crisis, the treasurer said.
</P>
<P>
The biggest spending measure in the budget is a 630 million
U.S. dollar, four-year plan to allow business to write off the
cost of replacing computer software to counter the year 2000
millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The budget maintains the 18 billion U.S. dollar offer for
five-year public hospital funding, representing a 15 percent
increase, although only the Queensland state and Canberra of its
six states and two territories accepted the offer.
</P>
<P>
Australia's official aid overseas during the next financial
year will be increased to 1.48 billion Australian dollars (931
million U.S. dollars) from 1.43 billion Australian dollars (900
million U.S. dollars) for financial 1997-1998, a real increase of
0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Papua New Guinea, Indonesia and Vietnam, the three largest
recipient nations of Australia's official aid in the current
financial year, are expected to maintain their positions by
receiving 201 million, 67 million and 44 million U.S. dollars in
aid respectively.
</P>
<P>
Australia's defense spending in the coming fiscal year would be
maintained at 10.9 billion Australian dollars (6.86 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Costello said the budget set Australia on a course to remain a
strong economy in the region, but more reform was needed,
including a shakeup of the tax system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0172 </DOCNO>
