<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Confident of Winning Five Golds in Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, China, May 12 (Xinhua) -- World champion Marion Jones
said she is confident of taking five gold medals in the 2000
Syndey Olympics after winning the World Fastest Women 100-meter
Race with a personal best of 10.71 seconds here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"My goal and my dream are to win five gold medals in Sydney
Olympic Games," she said, "I think it's very possible, if I stay
healthy and continue to have fun. If everything goes as it should."
</P>
<P>
The multi-talented athlete is not only the world number one in
the 100 and 200 meters, but also set a year's long jump best of
7.05 meters last week and did pretty good in the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
The time of 10.71 was not only her personal best, but also the
best since Florence Griffith-Joyner clocked 10.70 in Indianapolis
on July 17, 1988.
</P>
<P>
But Jones kept a low profile on when to break the world record
of 10.49, also set by Griffith-Joyner in 1988.
</P>
<P>
"I only think I can run faster, sub 10.70, that's my goal," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The basketballer-turned-sprinter has made remarkable progress
in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996 U.S. Olympic trials, she failed to qualify. But in
the 1997 Athens World Athletics Championships, she shocked the
world by taking the 100-meter title in 10.76, which was the year's
best.
</P>
<P>
She maintained the momentum this year, clocking 10.79 to win
the Osaka Grand Prix last Saturday, a day before she arrived in
this capital city of Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
Jones said the wonderful performance here was not because of
money, but because of the exciting atmosphere in the Chengdu
Stadium wherein the race drew about 20,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
"The reason that I had such wonderful performance was because
of you, because of the fans and because of the other competitors,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"I think I have been blessed to have a group of men who
surround me every day, my manager, my coach and my boy
friend. This does give me power."
</P>
<P>
But the American denied that she is the greatest female in the
world and admitted there is still a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
"I do not consider myself such a outstanding female in the
world ever because it's very early in my career. I have fun, I am
still young, I am only 22. We set up the races accordingly, so I
don't get burned out."
</P>
<P>
And she hoped to come to this lucky place. "Definitely, if you
invite me again, I love to come back. I love to come to this
wonderful situation to have another race next year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
