<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth of China's External Trade Slackened by Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The impact of the financial crisis
in southeast Asia on China's external trade has started to show
as the year-on-year growth rate of its trade volume in the first
four months dropping some 5.1 percentage points from last year's
figure.
</P>
<P>
A latest report from the Customs shows that China's foreign
trade volume from January to April was 97.48 billion US dollars,
up by 7.9 percent from the same period of last year, while last
year's year-on-year growth was 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Drastic devaluation of the currencies of southeast Asian
countries, Japan and the Republic of Korea (ROK), all China's
important trading partners, combined with China's own tax rebates
and exemption policies, resulted in an year-on-year exports growth
15.3 percentage points lower than last year's and an import growth
3.6 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
Customs figures show that China made an export volume of 56.19
billion US dollars, up by 11.6 percent over the same period of
last year, and an import volume of 41.29 billion US dollars, up by
3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Naturally, China's exports to southeast Asia, Japan and the ROK
dropped while imports rose, and the pattern just reversed with
the European Union and Russia. Both imports and exports to Hong
Kong and the United States kept growing.
</P>
<P>
State-owned industries and overseas-funded businesses accounted
for 48.8 percent and 48.1 percent in the trade volume for the four
months, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded processing businesses still played a leading
role in achieving growth in export, and the increase of imported
equipment by these businesses as part of its investment
demonstrated the effectiveness of tax rebates and exemption in
promoting overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The report also shows that exports and imports of primary goods
dropped by 15.1 percent and 12.8 percent respectively, while those
of industrial products rose by 16.1 percent and 7.7 percent
respectively. Exports of industrial products accounted for 89.2
percent of the total exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Curb In-Flow of Unskilled Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government urged
the country's construction industry on Tuesday to restructure
itself fundamentally and reduce its dependency on low-skilled
foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
"The construction industry must restructure itself
fundamentally. It cannot afford to continue with its high
dependency on low-skilled foreign workers," Minister for National
Development Lim Hng Kiang said at an awards presentation ceremony
for the construction industry.
</P>
<P>
He said the current economic climate presented "a good
opportunity for change", as sweeping changes would be more
difficult and disruptive to introduce at a time of frenzied
growth.
</P>
<P>
Between 1992 and 1997, the total number of foreign workers in
Singapore more than doubled from over 200,000 to over 450,000, the
minister said, adding that last year alone, the number rose by
more than 100,000.
</P>
<P>
While these figures include foreign workers in different
sectors of the economy, the bulk of the increase in the last two
years came from the construction sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the majority of these foreign workers were unskilled
and their productivity was "very low." The construction industry's
productivity level, measured in value-added terms, dropped from 4
percent in 1991 to minus 5.7 percent last year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In order to curb the in-flow of the unskilled foreign workers
into Singapore, Lim said the government Construction Industry
Development Board (CIDB) will introduce a Basic Skill Test for
foreign workers on August 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The test will cover generic competencies expected of a
construction site worker, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said a certain proportion of foreign workers being brought
into Singapore would have to pass this test before they are
allowed entry.
</P>
<P>
This test-taking requirement will start with 20 percent of all
foreign workers approved to be engaged by a contractor. The
percentage will be increased over the years until it reaches 100
percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the carrying-out of the Basic Skill Test, CIDB
will assist the industry in setting up more skill testing centers
in other labor source countries in addition to the existing ones
in China, Thailand and Myanmar, the minister said, but he stopped
short of naming those "other source countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
