<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Committed to Opening Up Financial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS) is committed to opening up the country's financial
sector to more competition, Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong,
who is also chairman of the MAS, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The MAS will allow market participants more free play to
innovate and take risk, he said at the opening of a two-day
seminar jointly hosted by the World Bank's Economic Development
Institute and the MAS.
</P>
<P>
The topic of the seminar is the importance of banking and
financial system soundness to economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
Lee said the Singapore government would undertake these reforms
through a steady series of incremental changes rather than in a
big bang, so that this approach would ensure there would be time
for institutions and participants to adjust and adapt.
</P>
<P>
He said that in order to reduce the risk of future crises,
governments must pursue prudent fiscal and monetary policies to
ensure sound macro-economic fundamentals, and bank regulatory and
supervisory systems must be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there must be greater disclosure and transparency,
while Asian countries must develop deep and broad capital markets,
and rely less on banking systems for financial intermediation, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
