<HEADLINE> Western Ministers Voice Concern Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RHODES, GREECE, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and defense
Ministers of the 28 Western European Union (WEU) member states
Tuesday voiced strong concern over the situation in the
Yugoslavian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In a "Rhodes Declaration" released after the two-day meeting,
the ministers said they were deeply concerned about the increasing
violence and growing polarization in Kosova.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been growing since February when Serbian police
clashed with ethnic Albanians of Kosovo who make up 90 percent of
the province's nearly two million population.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians have been calling for independence from
Yugoslavia and integration into Albania, but Belgrade stripped
Kosovo's autonomy in 1990 and strongly opposes independence.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said no changes should be made to the borders of
Yugoslavia, and urged the parties concerned to take immediate
steps to ease the tension and begin an "unconditional dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The ministers also expressed their readiness to promote a clear
and achievable path towards Yugoslavia's full integration in the
international community, should Belgrade take the steps needed to
launch substantive talks on Kosovo's political status.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade, however, is strongly opposed to any external
intervention in the Kosovo issue, and a recent referendum in
Yugoslavia backed the government's stance.
</P>
<P>
Liuis Maria De Puig, President of the WEU Assembly, said
Tuesday the body should now make a decision to prepare for
intervention which would take place only if the situation were to
deteriorate and if no negotiated settlement was possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
