<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis to Affect Australian Economy: Treasurer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Treasurer Peter
Costello predicted on Tuesday that the current Asian financial and
economic crisis would have a significant impact on the Australian
economy.
</P>
<P>
"The financial and economic crisis in Asia will have a
significant influence on the Australian economy in (the fiscal
year of) 1998-99," he told parliament when delivering his third
budget.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the influence, he said, Australia's economic
growth is projected to be 3 percent in the next financial year
starting on July 1, 1998, compared with the estimated 3.75 percent
growth rate for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Costello also predicted that the greatest ever financial crisis
in Asia was expected to trigger a 19.5 billion U.S. dollar blowout
in Australia's current account deficit, edging up to 5.5 percent
as a proportion of gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the Asian economic slowdown would reduce
export returns and when coupled with strong local demand would
lead to a temporary rise in the current account deficit. But the
blowout remained below the peaks in the 1980s and mid-1990s, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"The most obvious effects will be on export volumes and prices,
resulting in lower levels of exporters' incomes than would
otherwise be the case, with consequent impacts on output and
employment elsewhere in the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, as is already evident, the exchange rate (of the
Australian dollar against the U.S. dollar) will also be affected
by these developments."
</P>
<P>
"A lower exchange rate than otherwise would have occurred will
tend to lessen the impact of lower world demand and prices on
exporters' incomes while increasing the impact on consumers
through higher import prices."
</P>
<P>
The treasurer said that in the absence of the downturn in Asia,
Australia's economic growth in the financial year of 1998-1999
would have exceeded the 3.75 percent rate estimated for the
current financial year.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the uncertain Asian outlook, particularly in
Japan, were posing risks to the Australian economy in the coming
financial year and beyond.
</P>
<P>
The Asian crisis would not only have an adverse effect on
exports, but would affect confidence, resulting in slower growth
in business and consumer spending in Australia, the treasurer
said.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that in the midst of this turbulence,
Australia's growth would remain as strong as it could be, thanks
to measures taken by the current government to reduce the 6
billion U.S. dollar budget deficit it inherited from the previous
government two years ago, and Australia's healthy financial
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEU to Strengthen Relations With NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
RHODES, Greece, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and Defense
Ministers from 28 Western European Union (WEU) countries decided
Tuesday to further develop relations between the WEU and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In the Rhodes Declaration released after their two-day
conference here, the ministers reiterated that the Atlantic
alliance must continue to be the basis for collective defense
under the Washington treaty.
</P>
<P>
The alliance had begun a process of adaptation and reform, so
that it could more effectively carry out the full range of its
missions, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The process was aimed at strengthening and renewing the
trans-Atlantic partnership, including building a European Security
and Defense Identity (ESDI) within NATO which would enable all
European allies to take greater responsibility for their security
defense, it said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also reaffirmed that the union would continue
to take all necessary measures so that the ESDI could be grounded
on sound military principles and appropriate military planning.
</P>
<P>
The WEU was an essential element for the development of the
ESDI, ministers said, reiterating their commitment to continue
their efforts to enhance institutional and practical cooperation
with NATO.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1955, the WEU now has 10 full members, three
associate members, 10 associate partners and five observers.
</P>
<P>
The WEU is the European Union's defense arm. It has lived in
the NATO's shadow throughout the Cold War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
