<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Wholesale Prices Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's domestic wholesale prices had
dropped 2.3 percent in April from a year earlier, posting the
biggest fall since July 1987, the Bank of Japan (BOJ) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In April, the domestic wholesale price index, which measures
inflation on the level of corporate transactions and is considered
to foreshadow trends in consumer prices, stood at 97.6 against the
1995 base of 100.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale prices of electronics goods fell amid weakened
demand, and petroleum products prices declined due to sluggish
crude oil prices, the Japanese central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The latest data indicated that Japan is facing growing concerns
over deflation, or an economic contraction with falling prices,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the BOJ data, Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, played down concerns that Japan will be caught in a
deflationary spiral.
</P>
<P>
"You are going too far if you are talking about concerns of
deflation without watching inventory movements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the world's second largest economic entity, has seen its
economy grind to a standstill since 1991, and the recent financial
crisis reeling through Southeast Asia had been felt in Japan whose
exports have been badly hit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
