<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls for Dynamic Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
here Tuesday that Russia must adopt a dynamic foreign policy in
its endeavor to fulfill a range of important tasks, Itar-Tass
reported.
</P>
<P>
In a 45-minute address to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the
president said the major tasks included the preservation of
territorial integrity, the guarantee of national security, social
democratization and reforms and economic integration into the
world market economy.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also reportedly urged a speedy ratification of the
Second Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START-2) and the signing
of the START-3 agreement with the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said the signing of START-3 will be a breakthrough, a
complete balance with the United States in the levels and quantity
of strategic offensive weapons.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also stressed the importance of a balance between
security interests and practical economic possibilities.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia had finally been recognized as a market economy
and economic diplomacy has been gaining increasing significance in
Russian foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the formation of a multipolar world, Yeltsin said
the Group of Eight has taken shape and Russia is facing more
opportunities to exert a positive influence on the world community.
</P>
<P>
The president pointed out that Russian diplomats must be aware
that Russia had inherited a powerful military complex and an
economic foundation that was not solid from the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
He said it was the task of domestic and foreign policies to
deal with this imbalance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
