<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Hopes India Will Change Nuclear Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
Tuesday that India has "let us down" by staging nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who made the remarks in a speech delivered at Russia's
Foreign Ministry, said he hoped India would change its nuclear
stance.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia's relations with China, Japan and India have
experienced positive changes recently.
</P>
<P>
The President's Press Secretary, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, said
India's nuclear tests damaged the basis for the international
treaty on banning nuclear tests. He said Russia was upset with the
tests. He hoped India would join the international treaty on
banning nuclear test at an early date.
</P>
<P>
However, Vladimir Lukin, Chairman of the International Affairs
Committee of the Russian Duma, said India's nuclear tests should
not interrupt the traditional friendship between Russia and
India. He said Russia should not impose arms embargo sanction on
India.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Russian foreign ministry issued a
statement expressing Russia's "worry" about India's nuclear
tests. It hoped India would change its nuclear policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
