<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The Trade and Industry Committee of Yemeni House of
Representatives has recommended amendment to the Trade Code of
1991 to match the economic changes brought by the economic,
financial and administrative reforms employed three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom reported Tuesday that articles in
the code will be intensified on easing tax burdens of businessmen,
promoting trade, perfecting revenues collection system and
combating tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
TUNISIA -- A total of 1,650 foreign-funded firms and joint
ventures have settled down in Tunisia, with an investment of 4.5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Ministry of International Cooperation and
Foreign Investments said that these establishments, covering
Tunisia's industry, agriculture, services and tourism, have
created 150,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
TUNISIA -- Japan's Nissan motor company is to open a branch in
Tunisia soon in an effort to enhance its presence there.
</P>
<P>
A company official was quoted as saying that the move is
prompted by Nissan's conviction that Tunisia is a promising market.
</P>
<P>
Nissan has so far manufactured over 65 million cars and trucks
since its establishment in 1933, and is currently considered among
the most famous Japanese selling trade marks in Europe. 
</P>
