<HEADLINE> China to Introduce Professionals from Pittsburgh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- China's State Bureau of Foreign
Experts and the U.S. city of Pittsburgh today signed a protocol
relating to personnel exchanges and other areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Wan Xueyuan, director of the bureau, and Tom Murphy,
Pittsburgh's mayor, signed the protocol.
</P>
<P>
According to the protocol, the two sides will cooperate in
exchanges of professional personnel, research personnel and
trainees, and delegations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two parties support and encourage U.S.-China
university programs for master's degrees in business
administration.
</P>
<P>
Duquesne University in Pittsburgh established a cooperative
relationship with China's University of Political Science and Law
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The two universities have arranged four "summer programs" in
which foreign-law majors came to China to learn Chinese laws.
</P>
<P>
Before signing the protocol, Wang Guangying, vice-chairman of
China's National People's Congress Standing Committee, met with
Murphy and his party. 
