<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Offer Preferential Policies on High-tech Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- China's high-tech enterprises will
enjoy preferential policies, including tax exemptions, when
importing key technologies and facilities, a high-ranking economy
and trade official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"China's enterprises and foreign companies should enjoy the
same policies in the development of high-tech," said Long Yongtu,
vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation during a
speech for International Week featuring new and high-tech
industries, which opened Monday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Long said that high-tech investment projects, as long as they
are in line with China's related regulations, can be exempted from
Customs duties and import value-added taxes.
</P>
<P>
He added that the policies will be issued and implemented by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
In recent year, China's introduction of technologies focused on
such industries as resources, transportation, communications,
chemicals and raw materials. Currently, the country is
strengthening high-tech imports in the fields of optical fibers,
satellite communication, nuclear power and aerospace.
</P>
<P>
During the last seven years, China has signed more than 17,000
contracts for technology imports worth 66 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China's technology exports mainly include products in computer,
communications, electronics and life sciences. But China's
high-tech exports only account for 5.3 percent of the total
foreign trade volume.
</P>
<P>
According to Long, China will encourage research institutes and
universities to engage in international technological
trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
