<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEU Ministers Urge Substantial Role Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RHODES, GREECE, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and Defense
Ministers from 28 Western European Union (WEU) countries stressed
the body's substantial role in the development of a new European
security structure at the end of their two-day meeting, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration was issued as the meeting closed on the
Aegean island of Rhodes. It called for closer cooperation with
both the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The WEU, in its pivotal role between the EU and NATO, was an
important instrument permitting Europeans to shoulder their
responsibilities for Europe's security and defense, the
declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers reaffirmed the importance of the continued
development of a genuine European Security and Defense Identity
(ESDI), and of a greater European responsibility for security and
defense matters.
</P>
<P>
On cooperation between the WEU and EU, they said the WEU,
being an integral part of the development of the EU, supported the
EU in framing defence aspects of the Common Foreign and Security
Policy.
</P>
<P>
On the WEU-NATO relations, the ministers repeated that they
would continue their efforts to enhance institutional and
practical cooperation with NATO, which is considered the basis for
collective defense under the Washington Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The ministers urged the parties involved in the Kosovo issue to
take immediate steps to reduce tension and begin an unconditional
dialogue for the final settlement of the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were WEU Secretary-General Jose
Cutilheiro, President of the WEU Assembly Liuis Maria De Puig,
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana and EU Commissioner
responsible for Foreign Affairs Hans Van Den Broek.
</P>
<P>
Greece, which joined the WEU in 1995, at present holds the
organization's six-month rotating presidency.
</P>
<P>
The WEU, the EU's defense arm, groups Belgium, France, Germany,
Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Portugal, Spain, Britain and
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
