<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG, Indonesia, Vietnam Remain Biggest Recipients of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Papua New Guinea (PNG), Indonesia
and Vietnam, the three largest recipient nations of Australia's
official aid in the current financial year, are expected to
maintain their positions in the 1998-99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
PNG again gets the biggest single share of the Australian
overseas aid program for 1998-1999, with total estimated aid
funding of 320 million Australian dollars (201 million U.S.
dollars), the Australian government said in its budget unveiled
Tuesday for the coming fiscal year starting on July 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
That amounted to 21 percent of Australia's total official aid
worth 1.48 billion Australian dollars (930 million U.S. dollars),
Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said.
</P>
<P>
PNG, a country with a population of 4.2 million, became
independent from Australia in 1975.
</P>
<P>
PNG is followed by Indonesia, Australia's largest neighbor,
which is expected to receive 67 million U.S. dollars in aid from
Australia next year, 4.2 million U.S. dollars more than that of
the current financial year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam, a new market for Australia, is to get 44 million U.S.
dollars in aid from Australia, an increase of 1.3 million U.S.
dollars over the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Pacific Island countries are to receive a total of 82 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Downer said Australia will provide special funding in response
to the Asian financial crisis and the El Nino climate effect.
</P>
<P>
A new 3.6 million U.S. dollar Asia Crisis Fund will be
established to provide technical assistance to affected countries,
helping with economic governance and financial sector reform.
</P>
<P>
Emergency funding has been tripled to 21 million U.S. dollars
to enable Australia to respond quickly to help the victims of
droughts, cyclones and floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
