<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Hard to Lift China's Athletics out of Doldrums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, China, May 12 (Xinhua) -- To spend just 20 yuan (2.5
U.S. dollars) to watch world champion Marion Jones run 100 meters
in the world's first-ever fastest women race was a nice thing on a
cool summer afternoon?
</P>
<P>
"No, how can I be so stupid to see seven women run 10-plus
seconds?" said a taxi driver, "I prefer spending 200 yuan (25
dollars) for a first division soccer match."
</P>
<P>
Chengdu, capital city of Sichuan province, was the host venue
of Sichuan Quanxing, a second class team of China's 14-member
first division soccer league.
</P>
<P>
The world fastest women race, which ended this afternoon with
Jones prevailing with a personal best of 10.71 seconds, was a
newsmaker than a sports gala.
</P>
<P>
Over 250 journalists from Chinese and overseas media, including
AP, Reuters and AFP, have gathered here to cover the event, which
was similar to the 150-meter showdown last June between 100-meter
Olympic champion Donovan Bailey of Canada and American Michael
Johnson, double gold medalist in the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Zhangchi Public Relations Company, promoter of the event, took
Chengdu as the right place for them to publicize track and field
and cash in on it, since it was the hometown of China's fastest
woman Li Xuemei, who emerged as one of the world's best sprinters
last October in the Chinese National Games with a run of 10.79.
</P>
<P>
But it is hard for the inland province's inhabitants to know
the significance of such a commercial event.
</P>
<P>
"Track and field is the mother of sports. We hope this race
can boost China's track and field," said Shang Xiutang, vice
director of the Chinese Track and Field Adminstratitive Center, in
a pre-race news conference.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, two days before the race and the day when Jones
arrived here, Quanxing hosted a league match against Beijing
Guo'an with a sell-out home crowd of 40,000. Price of tickets in
blackmarket reached as high as 250 yuans (30 dollars).
</P>
<P>
"People know about soccer as little as they know about sprint,
but they prefer to enjoy themselves for 90 minutes in a soccer
match instead of 11 seconds for such a race," another taxi driver
said.
</P>
<P>
Every facet of information show that Chengdu has had China's
most prosperous soccer market since China introduced professional
soccer league in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"You can never expect sports fans to turn their eyes from
soccer to other events," he added.
</P>
<P>
Coincidently, the fastest women race was held in the home venue
of Quanxing soccer team. Right before the race began, players of
Quanxing, who came to watch the world champion's performance, were
greeted by a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
"Please cheer the women sprinters as you cheer the Quanxing
team," said an announcer in the speaker over the stadium.
</P>
<P>
Although there were 20,000 sitting on the stand, most of them
came with free tickets. An official from Chengdu Sports
Commission revealed that less than 3,000 tickets were sold.
</P>
<P>
"I was told that only 2,000 to 3,000 tickets have been sold,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
But Chinese Athletics Association (CAA) took the race as a
long-term investment rather than a make-or-break lucrative
business.
</P>
<P>
CAA president Lou Dapeng said: "Generally speaking, the race
was very successful. By accumulating experiences, we will be able
to host more successful world track and field competitions in the
future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
