<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discrepancies Cited in Philippine Election Returns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The National Citizens' Movement for
Free Elections (Namfrel), a private watchdog in the Philippines,
reported on Tuesday some "discrepancies" in the official election
returns provided by poll officials.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel is the sole non-governmental organization authorized by
the Philippine Commission on Elections to conduct a quick count of
the votes. It said it would release the final result of the
presidential election within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Namfrel Secretary General Guillermo Luz told a press conference
that some election inspectors who conducted the tabulation at the
precinct level failed to note and fill in the total number of
votes cast.
</P>
<P>
This was one of the factors for the slow reporting of the
initial results of the elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of them just left it blank when it came to the total
number of votes cast but the tally is there with respect to the
votes garnered by individual candidates," he said.
</P>
<P>
Luz cited two election returns on which the inspectors failed
to fill in the figures for the number of votes cast, the number of
voters registered, the number of voters who voted and the number
of ballots rejected.
</P>
<P>
In the said case, Luz said, Namfrel took the highest sum of
total votes cast for either president or vice president or the
highest ranking senator as the votes cast at the precinct.
</P>
<P>
"While this is not an exact number, it is the closest
approximation we can get for the votes cast. In fact, it'll still
be understated considering that there may be voters who did not
vote for president or vice president," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Luz said, the delay for the reporting of the initial
results was also caused by the failure of Namfrel volunteers to
get a copy of the election returns after some inspectors asked for
many requirements such as a letter of authority from Namfrel to
retrieve the document of election returns.
</P>
<P>
Luz said the identity cards of the volunteers bore the
authority to retrieve the said document.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of some 34 million registered voters Monday
cast their ballots at 175,000 precincts all over the country to
choose a new president, a vice president, 12 out of 24 senators,
260 members of the House of Representatives and thousands of local
officials.
</P>
<P>
As of 18:00 local time (10:00 GMT) Tuesday, Namfrel had counted
about 2.1 percent of the votes cast nationwide. Among the
presidential candidates, Vice President Joseph Estrada of the
Laban ng Makabayang Masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipino
Masses) took a commanding lead with 169,926 votes.
</P>
<P>
Senator Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party
led the other 8 vice presidential candidates with 185,097 ballots.
</P>
<P>
Monday's voting was generally peaceful and orderly despite the
fact that a failure of elections was declared in eight towns,
especially in Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 people were killed on the voting day. Compared
with 169 deaths in the 1992 presidential election and 210 deaths
in the 1995 congressional election, Monday's voting was the most
peaceful in the country's election history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
