<HEADLINE> Zhongguancun Falls Short as China's Silicon Valley (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Zhongguancun, a street full of
high-tech companies and international business franchises, is a
crowded computer supermarket rather than resembling Silicon
Valley, analysts said here today.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's Haidian High-tech Development Zone, with a street
featuring electronics products at the core, had more than 34
billion yuan (4.1 billion U.S. dollars) in turnover last year, 25
times 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, businesses around the street earned most of their
profits from the trade on computers and related products.
</P>
<P>
"Silicon Valley in the United States is based on scientific
research and high-tech manufacturing, however, most of the
business runners at Zhongguancun are focusing on computer trade,"
said Cao Gang, vice chairman of the Ziguang Group, affiliated with
the prestigious Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
"Zhongguancun is a big computer fair at most," said Yao Bing,
vice general manager with a computer company, "This is a far cry
from China's Silicon Valley."
</P>
<P>
Experts suggested reducing computer shops along the
five-kilometer-long street. They hoped that more jumbo enterprises
would combine scientific research, manufacturing and commerce in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, many businesses at Zhongguancun planned to upgrade
their companies. They are scheming new development strategies,
especially in information technology, automation, research on new
materials and life sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition on HK's History of Seaboard Defense Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A preview of the Hong Kong Museum
of Coastal Defense was opened Tuesday at the Hong Kong Cultural
Center, offering the citizens a chance to see the museum about
Hong Kong's 600-year seaboard defense history a year and a half
before its completion.
</P>
<P>
The new museum is located at the ruins of the Lei Yue Mun Fort,
which was a defense work built by the British army in the 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the exhibition, Kwong
Hon-sang, secretary for works of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), said that the SAR government has
preserved and maintained the historical relics, and has rebuilt it
into a museum for the benefit of the public, so that they may have
a better understanding of Hong Kong's coastal defense.
</P>
<P>
However, Kwong said, the history of Hong Kong's coastal defense
can be dated back to 600 years ago, when the Chinese navy in the
Ming dynasty fought against the invasion of the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The history of Hong Kong's coastal defense also includes the
period in which the Qing dynasty soldiers resisted the occupation
of Hong Kong by the British forces.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said the new museum, scheduled to be opened by the end of
next year, was undoubtedly a cultural contribution to the
community.
</P>
<P>
Besides its meaningfulness in history education, the museum
will become a new scenic spot for tourists and then enhancing Hong
Kong's tourism, Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
Kwong noted that the construction of the museum was no simple
task. "While it is necessary to preserve the invaluable historical
relics, it is also essential to make appropriate alternations and
provide additional facilities to meet modern architectural
standards," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the ceremony, Mok Ying-fan, chairman of the
Provisional Urban Council (PUC)'s Museums Select Committee, agreed
that construction of the museum was "a very demanding task as the
site is very rugged and strategic in nature".
</P>
<P>
"There are many complicated technical and architectural
problems to tackle, such as geotechnical structures, electrical
installations, preservation of the historical remains and natural
environment," Mok said.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the new museum will achieve world class
standard," Mok said.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the museum started in last October. The
site occupied 260,000 square meters, an area three times larger
than that of the Hong Kong Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Organized jointly by the Architectural Services Department and
the PUC, the 12-day preview comprises 24 panels featuring the
historical and architectural aspects of the museum.
</P>
<P>
The panels cover the history and changes of Hong Kong's coastal
defenses in the past 600 years and the important military features
such as the redoubt and the defense ditch.
</P>
<P>
In addition, two architectural models and a number of
historical relics are on display. One of the models gives and
overall aerial view of the museum and the other shows some
specific parts.
</P>
<P>
A video showing the historical background and the military
features by three-dimensional animation will be screened at the
exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhongguancun Falls Short as China's Silicon Valley (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Analysts estimated that the turnover by 2000 will double
today's figures with half of it from manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
At present, the most famous names of the 4,500 enterprises such
as Stone, Legend and Founder all focus on information
technology. The other three fields on their strategy list are
really new for Chinese entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Many institutions of higher learning and research institutions
are located near Zhongguancun. Some 36 enterprises, most of which
have university connections, earn more than 100 million yuan
annually. Seven listed as nation-level giant companies account for
40-to-70 percent of the domestic market share.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen started their computer trade in the mid-1980s. They
maintain their businesses on the street, but their net profits for
selling a single computer have plummeted to about 200 yuan from
over 10,000 yuan, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"We thought we could create a Silicon Valley at Zhongguancun 18
years ago but, in fact, we didn't even know what Silicon Valley
was at that time," said Chen Chunxian, a former research fellow
with the Chinese Academy of Sciences who began a business on the
street.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is to maintain the momentum of
technological innovation -- Silicon Valley is not a trade center,"
said Ni Guangnan, an academician of the Chinese Academy of
Engineering.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
