<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Aid Group Holds Mid-Term Review Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Bangladesh Aid Group
held a one-day mid-term meeting here Tuesday to review the
country's economic performance and reform progress, particularly
its privatization program.
</P>
<P>
The donors acknowledged the Bangladeshi government's success in
economic development, backed its efforts to maintain economic
stability, and urged further actions in reforming the country's
financial, executive and local government systems, Finance
Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria told a press conference after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Terming the meeting as "open, candid and friendly," Pierre
Landell Mills, World Bank resident director in Dhaka, said the
donors had a dialogue and exchanged views with the Bangladeshi
government.
</P>
<P>
The donors reached a strong consensus on what was to be done on
the part of Bangladesh, and obtained a commitment from Dhaka
regarding poverty eradication, economic reform and other issues,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh would gain an economic growth rate of 5.5 percent in
the current fiscal year ending June 30, with poverty declining,
investment rising and export growth increasing, a World Bank press
release said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, "slow progress in addressing critical issues such as
financial sector reform, privatization, and public administration
reform are depriving the country and its poor from taking
advantage of the potential gains of rapid economic expansion,"
said the release.
</P>
<P>
The donors urged the Bangladeshi government to speed up
administrative and financial reforms, and make faster progress in
privatization of state-owned enterprises, a separate World Bank
press release said.
</P>
<P>
The donors expressed their commitment to supporting the
country's initiatives in poverty alleviation, with particular
focus on reaching the poorest, it said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, chaired by Mills, was attended by senior officials
of the donors' missions here and senior Bangladeshi officials. A
full-scale Aid Group meeting, titled "Bangladesh Development
Forum," would be held in Paris in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Aid Group comprises 15 countries, including the
United State, Britain, France and Japan, and 12 international
organizations such as the Asian Development Bank, the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Rates in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are interbank
foreign exchange rates and the rate of the Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) (in rupees per unit):
</P>
<P>
Unit Interbank RBI
</P>
<P>
US dollar  rs. 39.76/77  reference rate rs. 39.78
</P>
