<HEADLINE> Britain Unveils Investment Plan for N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Tuesday unveiled an
economic strategy for Northern Ireland worth 315 million pounds
(520 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Finance minister Gordon Brown told an audience in Belfast that
the package would include a 150 million pounds (245 million
dollars) fund for new investment.
</P>
<P>
The money would be spent on transport, education and training
and housing, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
Brown is the only serving British chancellor of the exchequer
to visit Northern Ireland since the 1969 outbreak of guerrilla
conflict over British rule that has claimed more than 3,200
victims.
</P>
<P>
Brown said he and Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam,
together with leading business people, would visit the United
States soon in a bid to drum up further investment in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Before flying to Belfast, Brown told BBC radio the initiatives
were funded by "new money" from the British finance ministry. He
hoped other sources including the European Union and the United
States could follow suit to promote the province as an attractive
base for inward investment.
</P>
<P>
"That's the springboard for what I believe will be very
considerable investment from outside Northern Ireland in business
in Northern Ireland, and of course the generation of new
businesses indigenous to Northern Ireland as well." he said.
</P>
<P>
The British government already heavily subsidizes Northern
Ireland, which has been one of Britain's high unemployment
blackspots for decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
