<HEADLINE> Kuwait Receives New Oil Tanker from Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Oil Tankers Company
(KOTC) said it has received one of two modern oil tankers from
Hyundai Heavy Industries Company of Korea as part of the effort to
revamp its fleet.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti company's petroleum assistant undersecretary for
technical affairs and deputy board chairman, Hashem Al-Rifai, said
Tuesday that KOTC aims to replace old tankers with new ones in
line with the strategy to introduce modern vessels and equipment.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by Kuwait News Agency as saying saying the ship
has a capacity of 309,000 tonnes and equipped with sophisticated
devices for reading and printing maps, early-warning, safety and
oil transportation.
</P>
<P>
KOTC is the export arm of the state-owned Kuwait Oil Company
and now has four oil tankers, six gas tankers and 22 others for
transport of oil products.
</P>
<P>
Al-Rifai said the new tanker named Al-Sahia will join the
fleet this year and would be followed soon by another one called
Al-Shqaya in late June according to a contract with Hyundai.
</P>
<P>
The double-hull tanker, equipped with special devices to
minimize pollution, could sail at a record speed of 15.8 knots per
hour as shown in the test, he said.
</P>
<P>
The tanker was delivered at Hyundai basin in the south Korean
city of Ulsan Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
