<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Measures Against International Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
proposed on Tuesday a series of steps to control the threat from
terrorism, drug trafficking, illegal immigration and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
Just hours before his departure for Europe, Clinton unveiled
his International Crime Control Strategy today at the White House,
calling for 289 million U.S. dollars to help combat drug
trafficking and other border-crossing crimes.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will attend the G-8 economic summit in Birmingham,
England, starting on Thursday. The summit is to be attended by
leaders from France, Germany, Britain, Italy, Japan, Canada, the
U.S. and Russia.
</P>
<P>
At the G-8 summit, those nations will begin working on a plan
to cooperate on fighting international crime.
</P>
<P>
"We will work with other nations to create a worldwide dragnet
capability to promptly arrest and extradite fugitives from
justice," Clinton said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will work to ensure other nations are also ready to
fight international crime with global standards and goals,
training and technical aid, and programs to modernize criminal
laws elsewhere, added Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed that the U.S. work with its allies to share
information on growing crime syndicates to better derail their
schemes, and "we'll work with industries to protect against
computer crime."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. will strengthen border security with a
thousand new Border Patrol agents, new technologies, and stiffer
penalties to put more smuggling rings out of business.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
