<HEADLINE> EU Ban on Fish Import Costs Mozambique Dearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has lost nearly 240
million U.S. Dollars since the European Union imposed a ban on
Mozambique's fish import since this January, a Mozambican
minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Agriculture and Fishery Minister Isidora Faztudo told
the Noticias paper here Monday that the ban would cost Mozambique
more if Maputo could not find new markets.
</P>
<P>
Premier Pascoal Mocumbi last week said he hoped the EU would
cancel the ban as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has a yearly catch of prawns and fishes of about
20,000 tons, more than half of which have been exported to the EU
countries.
</P>
<P>
Cholera broke out in the country last August and since then
over 30,000 have contracted the disease and about 780 people have
died of it.
</P>
<P>
The EU said it would send experts to Mozambique in June to
inspect the production and hygienic conditions of the fish
processing industry in the country. 
</P>
