<HEADLINE> Dozens Lebanese Face Graft Charges in Port Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of Lebanese customs agents,
port middlemen and staff of freight companies will all stand
trial in a port scam, the Daily Star newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The accused, including 32 customs agents alone, will face
charges of forging import manifests, tariff evasion or seeking and
accepting bribes.
</P>
<P>
In a 109-page indictment, Beirut investigating magistrate Said
Mirza said the offences were revealed when customs inspectors
suspected that a shampoo shipment imported by Beirut Cooperative
Supermarkets had specifications different from those mentioned in
the manifests.
</P>
<P>
Investigations proved that the manifests and the stamps
applied to them were fake and that fees paid by the importer had
been pocketed by the indicted suspects, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
Later inquiries showed that the problem had started around the
beginning of last year when the port's customs department was
computerized.
</P>
<P>
Mirza said that at least 215 manifests out of 40,000 recorded
during that period were fake.
</P>
<P>
The total loss to the treasury has not been determined but the
indictment said that two of the fake manifests had deprived the
treasury of 41 million Lebanese pounds (about 27,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The magistrate said that he had recommended that the suspects
receive prison sentence raging between three months and seven
years with hard labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0237 </DOCNO>
