<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expects To Make Dunhuang Documents Available To Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Documents discovered at Dunhuang in
the last 100 years are expected to be open to the public thanks to
the efforts of scholars who want to study the unusual relics.
</P>
<P>
According to today's "Wenhui Daily", Hangzhou University has
started to compile the "Dunhuang Document Collection" in 30
million Chinese words.
</P>
<P>
Professor Rong Xinjiang of Beijing University's History
Department says that a large number of Dunhuang Documents from the
5th to the 10th centuries has been scattered about in Britain,
France, Russia, and Japan since they were discovered in in
1900. This has created many difficulties for those who wish to
study these relics, Prof. Rong says.
</P>
<P>
In the '60s and '70s, libraries in Britain, France, and China
began to make some of these documents more available, stimulating
greater interest in Dunhuang culture in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The Mogao Grottoes, popularly known as the Thousand Buddha
Caves, were carved in a 1,600-meter stretch of rock on the eastern
side of Mingsha Hill, 25 km to the southeast of the town of
Dunhuang, in today's Gansu Province, for the purpose of
propagating Buddhism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Trains Getting Rid of Styrofoam Food Boxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- China plans to replace the
styrofoam food boxes being used on trains with paper ones within 2
years to deal with the "white pollution" that has plagued the
railway lines.
</P>
<P>
As a first step, trains going to Beijing, Shanghai and
Guangzhou will use paper food boxes beginning on World Environment
Day, June 5.
</P>
<P>
Although China has used biodegradable boxes on trains since
July 1996, the 300 million boxes used every year still add a lot
to the "white pollution" that can be seen along China's railway
lines.
</P>
<P>
The paper boxes will be made from natural pulp and are hygienic
and hold the temperature of food well. They are also recyclable
and biodegradable and pose almost no threat to the environment,
according to one environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the environmentally-friendly boxes, more garbage
bags will be used and they will be dumped at designated places,
the Ministry of Railways says.
</P>
<P>
A recent environmental study by the National Patriotic Hygiene
Campaign Committee, the State Environmental Protection
Administration, and the Railway Ministry found that the "white
pollution" problem has eased up to some degree along railway
lines, and has almost been eliminated along the Beijing-Guangzhou
line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
