<HEADLINE> Chinese Pupil Hangs Himself because of School Punishment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A sixth-grade student in Urumqi,
the capital of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous region,
committed suicide after he was punished to go home from class for
"unruly" behavior.
</P>
<P>
The twelve-year-old Li Xingrui was told to go home shortly
after the class began on the morning of May 7 and to copy lessons
from his Chinese textbooks for failing to finish his homework
assignment, China Youth Daily reported today. When the boy cried
and pleaded with his teacher who was a model worker with some 20
years' teaching experience, the teacher then asked one of his
classmates to call his father, who was asked to take his son home.
</P>
<P>
Li was said to be unruly and was often criticised by teachers
for his poor classroom performance, and he never seemed to care
much about his lessons, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
China's education system has come under fire in recent years
for putting an unreasonable amount of stress and strain on exam
results, to the detriment of personal quality and cultivation.
</P>
<P>
And a number of suicides and a general outcry have prompted the
Ministry of Education to look into and reform on the primary and
middle school curricula and the university entrance examination
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
