<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Chocolate" for Livestock Invented in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- After six years of research, Chinese
scientists have invented a kind of nitrogen-building fodder --
called "chocolate for animals" -- which has proven quite useful in
helping livestock survive snowstorms.
</P>
<P>
The research was aimed to provide nitrogen-containing feed for
yaks and Tibetan sheep grazing in high country and cold areas,
especially where snowstorms occur, in a bid to help them lose less
weight and survive natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
From last winter to this spring, nearly a million head of
cattle and sheep in northwest China's Qinghai Province were
exposed to serious snowstorms, but most of them survived because
of large applications of the new feed, a brainchild of the
province's Academy of Animal Husbandry and Veterinary Science.
</P>
<P>
The brick-shaped hardtack, as local herdsmen call it, is made
of molasses mixed with wheat bran, non-protein nitrogen, maize,
detoxified rapeseed dregs and minerals, said Hu Linghao, director
of the province's Science and Technology Commission, who is in
charge of the research project. The fodder can also be used to
fatten livestock.
</P>
<P>
A trial feeding of yaks and Tibetan sheep for 200 days shows
that yaks that were given the new fodder during cold seasons lost
16 to 22 kilograms of less weight, while sheep didn't lose any
weight.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the survival rate of calves and lambs can be
raised by 20-to-30 percent when using the "chocolate," Hu
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
