<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top U.S. Cigarette Companies Increase Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Two largest U.S. cigarette
companies announced Monday that the wholesale price increases 5
cents per pack immediately.
</P>
<P>
"The price increase reflects the ongoing cost of conducting
business," said Richard Williams, spokesman of R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Corp.
</P>
<P>
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Corp. and Philip Morris Corp. said that
the price hike of 2.5 dollar per thousand cigarettes were
effective beginning from Monday.
</P>
<P>
A pack of cigarettes currently costs an average 1.95 dollar
including taxes at retail outlets nationwide, according to the
Tobacco Institute, an industry group.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth increase in 14 months by top cigarette
companies in the United States. The latest round of price hikes
began in March 1997, when the companies raised the price 5 cents a
pack, followed by a 7 cent boost in September, 2.5 cents hike in
January.
</P>
<P>
The January price hike came one day after a federal judge
approved Texas's record-setting of 15.3-billion-dollar settlement
with the industry, while Monday's announcement came after tobacco
companies reached a 6.6-billion-dollar settlement with Minnesota
and an insurance company Friday.
</P>
<P>
More states and insurance companies are seeking reimbursement
for health care costs associated with smoking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
