<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Strains of Cotton Seed Needed in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 12 (Xinhua) -- New types of cotton seeds should be
imported if Thailand wants to increase its cotton production and
thus boost its textile industry, the Bangkok Post reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although Thailand is a major textile and garment exporter, it
has to spend nearly 18 billion baht (474 million U.S. dollars)
each year on Importing the bulk of its cotton requirements, said
Somyos Jinsirivanich, president of the Thai Cotton Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
Thailand produced 25,810 tons of raw cotton last year and
expects a decline to 14,000 tons this year. The main reason for
the decline is that cotton planters are using lower quality seeds
while trying to cope with high costs of imported insecticides.
</P>
<P>
The yield of Thai cotton fields averaged 250 kilograms per rai
(0.16 hectares) compared with 800 kilogram in the United States
and Israel, both major cotton producers.
</P>
<P>
In view of the situation, the industry has asked the
Agriculture Ministry to approve funds for the import of new
strains of seed to improve production, Somyos said.
</P>
<P>
Somyos said his association wanted to import seeds developed by
Monsanto chemicals in the United States, using genetic
engineering.
</P>
<P>
Tests show that the seed could yield 350 kilograms per rai of
cotton in Thailand, and planters would need to spray insecticides
only three to four times during the four-month harvest season,
instead of 18 times currently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Briefs for Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The followings are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries released over
the past few days.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's non-traditional exports rose 11.8
percent in 1997 to 2.24 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a sharp increase of the country's
non-traditional exports. But coffee, banana and sugar remained
the traditional foreign exchange earners.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil reported 3.16 billion dollars of service and
technology exports in 1997, up 25 percent from the 1993 level.
</P>
<P>
However, this sector still posted a 1.84 billion dollars trade
deficit because five billion dollars were spent on importing
foreign services and technologies.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's Energy Ministry will invest a total of
69.7 billion pesos (8.17 billion dollars) this year to help boost
the country's oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Mexico ranks the fifth in the world in oil production and the
14th in natural gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The Venezuelan government will cut down public
spending by 3.43 billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
This is because government revenue will fall by 4 billions
dollars in the year due to the falling prices of oil, which is a
major income source of the government.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's orange production in the 1998-99 crop
season will go down 30 percent to 298 million boxes (40.8
kilograms per box) as compared with the output of the previous
season.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Exporters Association of Oranges attributed the
fall to the "El Nino" phenomenon and a disease attacking orange
trees.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil will export two billion liters of
anhydrous alcohol to the United States this year, nearly half of
its last year's production.
</P>
<P>
The country plans to export the same amount of anhydrous
alcohol to the United States in 1999. And the export is expected
to bring 800 million dollars in foreign exchange earnings for the
country annually.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, the world's number one anhydrous alcohol producer,
produced 4.75 billion liters in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
