<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Discover Genetic Connection with Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have announced
the discovery of at least 100 human genes, 40 of which have a
connection with some major diseases like cancer.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at Fudan University's College of Life Science in
Shanghai, held that the discovery may prove helpful in research on
liver cancer and embryo development.
</P>
<P>
They have chosen to register 80 genes with GenBank, an
international gene database in the United States, and 20 are
expected to be given international patents.
</P>
<P>
However, one geneticist involved in the research acknowledged
that Chinese research in this field is still not as advanced as
that in some foreign countries, and the exact functions of some of
the genes are remain unknown.
</P>
<P>
The project at the Genetic Engineering Laboratory has cost 100
million yuan (12 million US dollars) in its two months of work. It
was started by Fudan University and the New Huangpu Group
Corp. who also set up three genetic engineering companies last
week to speed up genetic research and apply their findings in new
products.
</P>
<P>
According to one earlier report, China plans to spend 7 million
yuan (843,000 US dollars) on studies of structures and functions
of the Chinese genome over the next four years, as part of its
Human Genome Project (HGP). Its purpose is to see to it that China
will be competitive in the field of genetics in the 21st century,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
