<HEADLINE> Myanmar Public Urged to Cut Down Use of Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar electric power
authorities have urged the public in the capital Yangon to cut
down the use of electricity in the face of power shortage in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's The New Light of Myanmar newspaper quoted Deputy
Minister of Electric Power Brigadier General Maung Maung as saying
that some power stations in the country have to reduce its
generation due to two consecutive years' scarcity of rain in the
northern part of the country and the water level at dams is low.
</P>
<P>
To strike a balance between power generation and use,
electricity is being supplied in turn in some areas in the
capital, the deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid urban development of Yangon in the last few
years, a wide gap has emerged between increasing electric power
demand and supply.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of April, the EL Nino phenomena has caused
sustainable high temperatures in Myanmar with Yangon reaching as
high as over 40 degrees centigrade, the highest in the hot season
in 30 years. This has led to more power demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
