<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Receive 100 Million Dollars for Chernobyl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Bank for Reconstruction
and Development (EBRD) has promised a loan of 100 million
U.S. dollars to reinforce the 12-year-old sarcophagus encasing the
Chernobyl nuclear reactor.
</P>
<P>
Under two agreements signed here between EBRD Vice-President
Joachim Jahnke and Yuri Kostenko, minister of Environmental
Protection and Nuclear Safety, the loan will be disbursed from the
EBRD-managed Chernobyl shelter fund and be used to keep the
concrete cover in a proper condition.
</P>
<P>
The EBRD is now holding its annual meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The crumbling shelter over the No.4 reactor, which exploded in
1986 in the worst nuclear accident in history, still contains
about 150 to 210 tons of fissionable fuel.
</P>
<P>
Experts said it will cost around 750 million dollars to repair
the concrete shell.
</P>
<P>
To date, the Group of Seven industrial powers -- Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States --
have approved a 300 million dollar grant to help the project and
the European Union agreed to contribute 100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government will allocate 150 million dollars for
the project over the next seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
