<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vote Counting in Philippines Slow at City Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- As official counting in the
Philippines is still continuing slowly Tuesday at the municipal or
city level, unofficial results show Vice President Joseph Estrada
is leading in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Official counting started immediately after the polls closed at
15:00 (0700 GMT) Monday, but was conducted at a very slow pace. So
far, the counting is still at the municipal or city level,
officials of the Commission on Elections said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The latest initial results from the Commission on Elections
cannot show significantly who is really leading in the
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
But according to the latest unofficial partial results provided
by the Namfrel (National Citizens Movement for Free Elections),
Vice President Joseph Estrada, standard bearer of the opposition
Laban ng Makabayang masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipinos
Masses), is leading with 21,071 votes.
</P>
<P>
He was followed by Emilio Osmena, candidate of the Progressive
Movement for Devolution of Initiative, with 16,941 votes, and
former Manila mayor Alfredo Lim of the Liberal Party trailed third
with 9,572 votes.
</P>
<P>
Other presidential candidates include Speaker Jose de Venecia,
who was anointed by President Fidel Ramos as the standard bearer
of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party, and senator Raul Roco of Aksyon
Demokratiko (Democratic Action).
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Imelda Marcos, who withdrew from the presidential race two
days before the general elections, received 389 votes, as her name
still appeared on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
The Namfrel is the sole non-government organization authorized
to conduct the unofficial quick count.
</P>
<P>
The official vote counting has been continuing very slowly.
After the counting at the precinct level, election inspectors will
turn over the election returns to the municipal or city level.
</P>
<P>
The total election returns will be recorded and tabulated and
then given to the provincial level.
</P>
<P>
The forms will then be forwarded to the House of
Representatives for the counting for the presidential and vice
presidential positions, while the Commission on Elections will
count the votes for the congressional posts.
</P>
<P>
The process is expected to take four weeks. But the Namfrel can
release the unofficial final results within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Voting for Monday's national and local elections was held in a
"generally peaceful and orderly manner" with a heavy voter turnout
across the country except for some areas where polling was marred
by violence and election irregularities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commission on Elections, about 80 percent of
the 34 million voters turned out and cast their ballots to choose
a president, a vice president, 12 out of 24 senators, 260 members
of the House of Representatives and more than 17,000 local
officials and councilors.
</P>
<P>
The voting was "generally peaceful and orderly", the Commission
on Elections said.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures showed that a total of 13 people were killed
all over the country in Monday's elections, bringing to 49 the
death toll in election-related violence since election campaigns
began in February.
</P>
<P>
However, compared with the previous elections including those
held in 1992 and 1995, the polls may be the most peaceful and
orderly in the country's election history, poll watchers said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 elections, about 169 people were killed in
election- related violence while in the 1995 senate election 210
people died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
