<HEADLINE> Philippines' Gross International Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' gross international
reserves (GIR) reached 11.1 billion U.S. dollars as of last week,
the highest level since the start of the financial crisis in the
country last July, the newspaper Today said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is the highest level achieved since July 1997 when the
regional currency crisis started," Gabriel Singson, governor of
the central bank of the Philippines, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The GIR, up 2.3 percent from last month's 10.8 billion dollars,
was boosted by the 291-million net proceeds of the National Power
Corp. Yankee bond issue, which were deposited in the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The GIR, which include the central bank's holdings of gold,
dollars and other foreign currencies, are equivalent to two and a
half months of imports of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
According to Singson, the bigger official reserves were made
possible by the central bank's decision not to intervene in the
foreign exchange market when the peso came under renewed
speculative attack recently.
</P>
<P>
But Singson said the central bank is prepared to adopt measures
to defend the Philippine currency if speculations against it
continue in the coming days -- "a possible scenario considering
the continuing political turmoil in Indonesia." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
