<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech, Chinese Army Leaders Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, May 11 (Xinhua) -- China, which pursues a defensive
military policy, will reduce its armed forces by 500,000 men in
three years, a visiting senior Chinese military officer said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fu Quanyou, chief of the General Staff of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army, told his Czech counterpart Jiri Sedivy that China
does not station troops or establish military bases abroad, nor
does it set up military alliances with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Fu, also a member of China's Central Military Commission, said
that China opposes hegemonism and power politics. China holds that
countries, no matter how big or small, should be treated equally,
he added.
</P>
<P>
On the international situation, Fu said the trend toward
multi-polarization is of great significance to worldwide peace and
development.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan issue, Fu affirmed that Taiwan is sacred
territory to China which opposes any attempts to create "two
Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Fu also exchanged views with Sedivy on
strengthening friendship and cooperation between the armed forces
of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Fu said that a fundamental conflict of interests does not exist
between China and the Czech Republic. The further development of
the traditional friendship between the two countries and the two
armies will serve the fundermental interests of the two
peoples. It will also encourage peace, stability and development
throughout the region and eventually the whole world.
</P>
<P>
Sedivy agreed and said there had been fruitful high-level
exchanges between the two armies in recent years. He hoped to
continue promoting such exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Sedivy also accepted Fu's invitation to visit China.
</P>
<P>
Fu arrived in Prague on Friday for a five-day visit to the
Czech Republic, the third leg of his four-nation tour. Fu's next
stop will be Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
