<HEADLINE> U.S. Attorney General Requests Independent Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Attorney General Janet Reno
Monday requested an independent counsel to investigate whether
Labor Secretary Alexis Herman engaged in influence peddling or
solicited illegal campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
Reno's decision to seek a seventh independent counsel for a
high-ranking member of the Clinton administration was relayed to a
special court late Monday and described in a brief court document
that was made public.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors and FBI agents during five months of preliminary
inquiry have neither corroborated a range of allegations made by a
businessman against Herman nor found other evidence to question
her actions, justice department officials said.
</P>
<P>
The primary allegation was that, as a White House aide during
the first Clinton administration, Herman took kickbacks for
helping a friend's clients. Herman has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton maintained his confidence in Herman,
"and in her ability to set whatever these allegations are behind
her," White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Monday. "She's
doing a spectacular job as secretary of labor."
</P>
<P>
Some Justice officials recommended Reno request appointment of
an outside prosecutor because the independent counsel law requires
that step when she is unable to resolve any specific, credible
allegations of federal felonies within 150 days, said department
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Other Justice officials apparently doubted that the remaining
unresolved matters were specific and credible enough to require an
independent counsel, according to news reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Pollution Worsens in Italy's Big Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Air pollution in Italy's big cities is
getting worse despite declining urban populations, the Italian
Statistics Bureau (ISTAT) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Urban population in large cities have been decreasing over the
last decade, with Milan down by 25 percent and Naples 30 percent,
according to ISTAT.
</P>
<P>
The decrease is the result of emigration to the suburbs where
housing is cheaper and the environment better, but suburban
dwellers still drive their own cars to work in city centers.
</P>
<P>
This trend has resulted in more cars on the road, and heavier
air pollution.
</P>
<P>
ISTAT said the government was partly responsible for the
worsening air pollution because it failed to increase public
transport services as more people moved to suburbs. In Milan,
about 900,000 people commute to work every morning, but only a
third take public vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The railway sector should be blamed as well, ISTAT said. It had
canceled many suburban stops for the sake of increasing speed,
which also contributed to the increase in private cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Warns of Grassland Deterioration in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official of the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region in north China has warned local
people of the serious deterioration of the grassland in the region.
</P>
<P>
Yunlongbu, president of the regional government, said that at
present the region's total land area suffering from
desertification, salinization, soil erosion and grassland
deterioration, accounts for 1.18 million square kilometers,
representing half of the region's total land area.
</P>
<P>
The region's area of serious soil erosion is 186,000 square
kilometers, or 15 percent of the region's land space. The region
has more than 3,800 hectares of seriously deteriorated grassland,
according to Yunlongbu. A month ago a sandstorm hit Alxa League in
the central portion of the region, causing an economic loss of
millions of yuan.
</P>
<P>
The region is also threatened by activities involving random
felling of trees and converting grassland to farming.
</P>
<P>
To curb such a situation, the region worked out a plan for
cross-century ecological protection and construction in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, ecological deterioration will be under
control in the next 13 years through tree-planting, building water
and soil conservation projects and converting farmland into
pasture for raising domestic animals. Through another 40 years of
effort, the region aims to set up an environment which is
compatible with the sustained development of the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
