<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions of Students May Quit Schools in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- About eight million elementary and
junior high school students in Indonesia may have to drop out of
school because of the prolonged economic crisis, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
The latest prediction was much higher than the first estimates
of only 2.8 million students (to quit school) made in the early
months of the crisis last year, Deputy Chairman of the National
Development Planning Board Hidayat Syarief told a seminar Monday
in Bogor, 60 kilometers south of Jakarta, reports reaching here
Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
He said the prolonged economic crisis was also expected to
cause an increase in the infant mortality and maternal mortality
rates and malnutrition among children in the future.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the economic crisis, more and more children are
expected to drop out of school, suffer malnutrition and various
diseases, which will put their lives at risk. And this condition
will certainly affect the quality of Indonesian human resources in
the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that many parents in rural areas will also be forced
to remove their children from school because the children would be
needed to help supplement the family's dwindling income.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the government and the public should adopt a
sense of crisis and take immediate action to prevent a high
dropout rate.
</P>
<P>
The government recently increased the minimum working age to 15
from 10 in an endeavor to make the nine-year compulsory school
program a success and to send about two million child laborers to
school under the National Foster Parents Movement.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is experiencing the worst economic crisis in three
decade. The rupiah (national currency) has lost more than 70
percent of its value against the U.S. dollar since July last year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
