<HEADLINE> Death Toll of Thai Cable Car Crash Climbs to 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A six-year-old boy succumbed to his
wounds Monday, raising the death toll of Sunday's cable car
accident in the northern Thai province of Chiang Mai to three, the
Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The boy suffered several serious wounds from the plunge of the
cable car at Phra That Koi Suthep Temple close to Central Chiang
Mai town.
</P>
<P>
The steel wire used to pull the two cable cars snapped Sunday,
sending the two vehicles plunging 50 meters to the foot of the
Phra That Koi Suthep Hill.
</P>
<P>
After inspecting the cable car system, local officials
concluded that overloading caused the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Each vehicle is designed to carry 14 passengers per trip, but
the two cars were found to serve a total of almost 40 people
before the plunge.
</P>
<P>
Sunday was the Visakha Puja Buddhist Holiday when a large
number of worshippers traveled to the temple, which is considered
to be a highly venerated and most visited religious place in the
province, to perform religious ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
Chiang Mai police chief Anudit Atthsart said the police
arrested the cable car operator and the mechanic for recklessness
leading to the deaths.
</P>
<P>
Chiang Mai Governor Pravit Sihasophon Monday ordered the temple
to close its cable car system permanently despite its negative
effect on tourism.
</P>
<P>
Another 35 people were injured in the accident, many of whom
are still being treated at three hospitals in the northern
province.
</P>
<P>
The plunge is the second failure of the cable car system after
a similar accident occurred in July last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
