<HEADLINE> Australia Condemns India's Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Australia said Tuesday it strongly
condemned India for carrying out three underground nuclear tests
this week and is considering further action against India.
</P>
<P>
Australian Foreign Affairs Minister Alexander Downer Tuesday
said, "The Australian government strongly condemns what India has
done," according to Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC)
Radio.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn India unreservedly for taking this decision to
detonate nuclear devices," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is in total defiance of the will of the international
community. Over 140 countries have signed a comprehensive test ban
treaty," he said.
</P>
<P>
"India is a country which apparently wants to develop a nuclear
weapons device to escalate tensions in South Asia," the foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Downer demanded a meeting with India's High Commissioner Gopal
Parthasarathy to Australia to express Australia's anger at the
blasts.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Australia's High Commissioner to
India Rob Laurie would be instructed to deliver the Australian
government's condemnation of the tests to the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the high commissioner would also be recalled
immediately for consultations on the kind of action Australia
could take in response.
</P>
<P>
The move is considered here by analysts as the strongest
possible diplomatic protest, short of cutting off bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Australia would be consulting with its "friends and allies
around the world", including the United States, Canada and the
Europeans and countries in Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
India's one-month-old government outraged neighboring Pakistan
with the tests in a remote desert, about 500 km southwest of the
Indian capital New Delhi, the Australian Associated Press said
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
