<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Strategy Benefits Foreign Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Confronted with a new world
situation created by the Southeast-Asian financial crisis, China
is stressing a new strategy in its bid to ensure the
implementation of foreign-trade goals.
</P>
<P>
Known as the "broadly based foreign-trade strategy", it aims to
strengthen government support, urge more enterprises to directly
engage in foreign trade, and diversify trade sources, market
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Though the situation is tough, China has vowed to reach 200
billion U.S. dollars in exports this year, which represents a 10
percent year-on-year increase. Shi Guangsheng, the new minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation, has repeatedly stressed
since his tenure began that the new strategy will be a major means
to cope with the situation.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts noted that the new strategy can help step up
reform in the existing foreign-trade rights approval system and
bring more foreign-funded enterprises into trade operations.
</P>
<P>
As an obvious change, while the central and local governments
have been cautious in granting foreign trade rights, now many
local governments are actively encouraging qualified enterprises
to apply for such rights and are relaxing the approval
requirements.
</P>
<P>
Previously, foreign-funded enterprises were only entitled to
export their own products. Now, they are being allowed to form
solely-owned or joint venture foreign-trade companies.
</P>
<P>
Some people are worried that Chinese foreign-trade companies
will face even stiffer competition and there will be more losses
in the country's foreign-exchange earnings when foreign-funded
trade companies are set up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Strategy Benefits Foreign Trade (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nevertheless, quite a number of experts acknowledged that the
contributions made by overseas-funded companies to China's exports
should be duly recognized.
</P>
<P>
One major step in the ongoing reform of the foreign-trade
structure is to replace the longtime practice of administrative
approval-and-examination system with a registration system for
granting foreign-trade rights. Such rights are being extended to
more enterprises, including foreign-run and private firms. By the
end of this year, the number of enterprises with foreign-trade
rights is expected to top 10,000.
</P>
<P>
Li Yushi, a renowned foreign-trade expert, said he believes
that the government's macro-economic policy, reforming both the
operating mechanism of foreign trade and import system are three
major issues that will determine the future of China's foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
The relatively high tariff level, the value-added tax levied on
imported goods and stringent administrative management of imports
have affected the importation of advanced technology and equipment
and the import trade as a whole, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li called for transforming the import structure and expanding
imports to sharpen the competitive edge of China's export products.
</P>
<P>
In its effort to simultaneously expand imports and exports, the
Chinese government dramatically cut the tariff in October last
year, and in January this year resumed the reduction and exemption
of import taxes on items needed by foreign-funded enterprises and
key projects.
</P>
<P>
The effort in this regard has helped to spur a 2.5 percent rise
in imports in the first quarter of this year. And experts forecast
that imports can grow by 10 percent for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
Li Yushi also predicted that China will further reduce the
scope or remove the administrative management on import products,
cut import quotas, reduce or remove value-added taxes on imports,
and further cut tariffs when conditions are mature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0295 </DOCNO>
