<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Public Shocked by Crimes of Unit '731' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 12 (Xinhua) -- People in Shanghai expressed shock
after seeing an exhibition this month showing evidence of the
crimes of Unit "731" of the wartime Japanese army.
</P>
<P>
"It's so frightening. I don't know why the Japanese army did
that to Chinese," said Xu Ming, a primary student in grade three,
after seeing the exhibition with his mother.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot forget it for all my life that when I was a little
boy, I witnessed how the Japanese soldiers threw germ bombs to
villagers and most of villagers died of the plague," recalled an
old man, whose hometown is Ningbo in east China's Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
A teacher from Shanghai Foreign Language University said that
the exhibition brought to light the evidence of atrocity by
Japanese militarists. Nobody should forget history, the teacher
said.
</P>
<P>
The one-month exhibition, the first of its kind in China, was
prepared by the Museum of Evidence of Crimes of Unit "731" located
in Harbin in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, and will
tour other cities including Ningbo, Guangzhou, Haikou, Hong Kong
and Seoul, capital of the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Unit "731" belongs to the Japanese aggressor troop's Kwantung
Army, with its headquarters based in Harbin during World War
II. The unit received a bad reputation for manufacturing germ
weapons based on experiments on living people.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 Chinese people were used for germ experiments
by Unit "731," according to a Japanese army official in charge of
germ experiments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
