<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Sees Hottest First Quarter Since 1866, Worldwatch Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Temperatures registered over the first
three months of this year were the highest the world has seen
since 1866, according to Lester Brown, chairman of the
Washington-based Worldwatch Institute.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Rome to present the prestigious environmental
observatory's annual report -- The State of the World, Brown said
that 1997 was the hottest year since 1866, so it remains to be
seen whether the average for all 12 months of 1998 beats last year.
</P>
<P>
He said 1997 was already the hottest year since 1866 in
absolute terms and 1998 is heading down the same
path. "Temperatures have risen strongly in the first quarter of
the year, and the overall picture is dramatic."
</P>
<P>
According to Brown, all-time highs were recorded last year for
carbon dioxide emissions claimed as a major cause of the
greenhouse effect as well as the concentration of carbon dioxide
in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Energy production and transport are the two main culprits for
carbon dioxide emissions. "Scientists and environmentalists have
long known that the economy cannot expand infinitely without
endangering the ecosystem," said Brown.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the exponential growth of the world economy as
the major cause of the destruction of the world ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
Brown said the world's economic growth in 1997 was the same as
for the whole century of the 1600s, and the consumption of
resources has risen sixfold since 1950.
</P>
<P>
"Water and wood consumption has tripled and the consumption of
fossil fuels has quadrupled," he said. "This consumption of
resources is a cause of stress for the planet."
</P>
<P>
He said the "stress" includes a reduction in fishery resources,
the loss of 16,000 hectares of forests a year, and the loss of
many animal and vegetable species.
</P>
<P>
"Four mammals out of every 100 risk extinction, and these
include our nearest relations in the animal world above all,"
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out three great signs of "stress" in 1997: the
parching of the Yellow River in China, the fires in Indonesia and
the great heat around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Praises Russia's Cabinet Shakeup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
national security advisor Sandy Berger said on Monday that Russian
President Boris Yeltsin's recent cabinet shakeup is a bold step
that produced "probably the most reformist government" in seven
years.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin "made a gamble and won," Berger told a briefing on the
eve of Clinton's departure for a summit meeting of the G-7
countries plus Russia in Birmingham, Britain, where Clinton and
Yeltsin are expected to meet.
</P>
<P>
It will be Clinton's first meeting with Yeltsin since the
Russian president fired his cabinet on March 23. Former Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin was replaced by 35-year-old Sergei
Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
"I think that President Yeltsin does have a grip on power, does
have control of his government," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
"I think he took a rather bold action... in dismissing a
government. He felt it was not moving swiftly enough toward
meeting the... economic needs of his people," Berger noted.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has assembled a new government that is young and "does
not carry enormous baggage, that has generally been pragmatic and
committed to reform," Berger said. "I find that very encouraging."
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that Kiriyenko was so young was "not
necessarily a handicap when you're talking about trying to remake
a system which has been frozen for all of those years in a command
economy."
</P>
<P>
Further, Berger said Yeltsin's other deputies "are all men of
enormous competence and professionalism."
</P>
<P>
Berger said Russia still faces formidable problems in expanding
its economy, attracting investment, collecting taxes and meeting
other challenges.
</P>
<P>
"We want to help them do that, but I think in many ways the
events of the last month suggest that President Yeltsin made a
gamble and won," he said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the White House's warm assessment sets a
positive tone for the summit between Clinton and Yeltsin scheduled
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Since they met at last June's summit in Denver, relations
between Washington and Moscow have been strained by divisions over
Iraq and Kosovo, and the U.S. push to expand the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO). 
</P>
</TEXT>
