<HEADLINE> Mexico Deports 40 Italian Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Mexico deported 40 Italian
human rights observers and banned them from returning to the
country for showing disrespect and contempt for Mexican laws and
regulations, a statement issued by the Interior Ministry said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
A group of 135 Italian observers, including the 40 expelled,
were allowed to visit Mexico on May 1-10 to observe the situation
of indigenous people living in the southern state of Chiapas, some
1,000 kilometers from Mexico City, the capital.
</P>
<P>
The 40 Italians, expelled by the Mexican government on Monday,
refused to leave Mexico after their visas expired, the ministry
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The acts and deeds attributable to the foreigners, who did not
leave Mexican territory in the fixed period of time, made their
presence in the country inconvenient."
</P>
<P>
The expulsion is reportedly based upon article 33 of the
Mexican Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government sent a special flight to Rome Monday
morning with the 40 deported Italians on board. 
</P>
