<HEADLINE> Sino-Vietnamese Border Trade Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- A 13-household village of Pingxiang
city in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region is now
crowded with buildings, shops, restaurants, and dancing halls --
all because of thriving border trade.
</P>
<P>
Puzai Village is only one of many examples of the prosperity in
doing trade along the Sino-Vietnamese border. Heavily laden
trucks come and go through the village, carrying goods from both
sides.
</P>
<P>
A local border trade official said that Puzai receives
3,000-to-4,000 trucks every day. Vietnamese traders bring local
products or seafood to exchange for Chinese clothing, cosmetics,
and farm-use plastic sheeting.
</P>
<P>
The region has opened four state-level ports, eight regional
ports, and 25 border trade areas like Puzai along the
Sino-Vietnamese border. It had a little more than 3 billion yuan
in border trade volume last year.
</P>
<P>
Villagers have considerably improved their living conditions by
doing border trade, a Customs official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
