<HEADLINE> Canadian Man Charged with Hijacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian man who attempted to
hijack an airplane to the U.S. Sunday night has been charged with
attempted hijacking and five counts of assault, reports said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old man from the city of Toronto appeared in court
Monday where he was charged and ordered to have a psychiatric exam.
</P>
<P>
Elgin Barrett is scheduled to return to court May 20, according
to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Yelling "I have a bomb," the man raced late Sunday night
through a parked airliner and demanded to be flown to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested in the cockpit of the Air Luxor L1011 aircraft
shortly after the attempted hijack. Nobody of the 256 people on
board was hurt in the hijack attempt.
</P>
<P>
Police said the man locked himself in the cockpit but was
distracted just long enough for a crew member to unlock the door
and allow police to rush in to subdue him.
</P>
<P>
The whole incident was over in a matter of minutes. The plane
was able to leave for Lisbon, Portugal, after a three-hour delay.
</P>
<P>
All the man carried was only a black gym bag which had only
clothes and a CD player.
</P>
<P>
That's what made people thought he had a bomb. "The people on
the plane were just virtually in shock," police said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Transport Minister David Collenette was reported to
say that he was pleased with the way the situation was handled.
</P>
</TEXT>
