<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dramatic Changes Brought to Jianghan Plain Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Transferring land leased from the
government to agricultural companies and turning into farm workers
with fixed salaries, that is the new way of life for thousands of
farmers in the Jianghan Plain, a major grain producer in central
China.
</P>
<P>
Different from their counterparts in other parts of China,
farmers in the Jianghan Plain, or the plain between the Yangtze
and Han rivers in Hubei Province have abandoned the traditional
way of farming -- on small individual plots.
</P>
<P>
The 356 farmer families in Wengang Village by Mazi Lake have
200 hectares of rice fields. They transferred the use right of 93
hectares to the Zhengchang Company in exchange for seven million
shares in the company. All the families are share-holders of the
company, and the farmers on the 93 hectares of land have become
employees of the company.
</P>
<P>
So far, about one sixth of 442,000 hectares of arable land on
the plain have been transferred to agricultural companies, and the
people who farm it have become employees of the companies,
according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The Tianfa Group Co. Ltd, a listed company, invested 400
million yuan (48 million US dollars) to build a salad oil factory
in Jingzhou City and a fine rice plant in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
The China Lantian Co. Ltd injected 320 million yuan (38.6
million US dollars) into the development of aquatic resources on
Honghu Lake, one of the biggest freshwater lakes in China; about
30,000 local farmers have benefited from this.
</P>
<P>
Overseas companies have also invested in the plain, and both
overseas and domestic businesses have invested a total of two
billion yuan (241 million US dollars) in local agricultural
projects. Some 100,000 farmers are employed by the companies.
</P>
<P>
This trend will boost the potential of agriculture in China,
according to economists. However, Liu Keyi, an official in charge
of economy in Jingzhou City, warned that companies based in cities
do not have a good understanding of the market for agricultural
products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
