<HEADLINE> Beijing to Utilize More Invention Patents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Realizing the economic value of
Beijing's great number of invention patents still represents a
great challenge for Beijing's municipal authorities, today's
Beijing Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Wang Youpeng, professor and director of the Beijing Patent
Administration Bureau, was quoted as saying that 80 percent of
last year's 1,674 invention patents have not been put into use.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Beijing submitted 1,677 inventions for patent
registration, far ahead of other Chinese regions (Shanghai:484,
Guangdong Province:680 and Tianjin:257).
</P>
<P>
Wang explained that the main obstacle for putting more
inventions into use is the people's poor awareness of the
importance of patents.
</P>
<P>
Wang said his bureau plans to set up a center especially for
experiments making products using patented inventions.
</P>
<P>
The bureau will also enhance publicity of the importance of
patents this year, in addition to the organization of some
research programs for related official.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released by China's National Patent
Administration Bureau, among the 33,666 invention patents approved
in 1997, 20,968 were submitted by foreign researchers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Urged to Overhaul Environment Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Italy's main ruling party, the Left
Democrats (DS), on Monday urged the government to give the
environment ministry with extended powers, enabling it to prevent
disasters like the fatal mudslides in southern Italy last week.
</P>
<P>
A statement, overwhelmingly approved by the DS, proposed
creating, within six months, a single Environment and Land
Ministry which will be responsible for land protection.
</P>
<P>
"We want to reform the national government according to the
model used in other European countries," said DS leader Massimo
D'Alema. "On the one side you'll have the environment and the
land, on the other major infrastructure."
</P>
<P>
He said the present system, under which the Public Works
Ministry is responsible for land protection and infrastructure,
was irrational.
</P>
<P>
The DS proposal follows complaints by Environment Minister Edo
Ronchi, of the Green Movement, that his ministry is deprived of
any real power to protect the land and prevent disasters happening
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
Ronchi said he was tired of writing a report and sending it off
to other ministries every time there was a flood or a landslide.
</P>
<P>
"I think the ministry should be given the powers to protect the
environment," he said. "Otherwise, what's its purpose?"
</P>
<P>
The DS proposal also asked other ministries with influence over
the land -- the transport and agriculture ministries -- to take
land protection into account when formulating and executing
policies.
</P>
<P>
Land protection has become a burning issue in Italy since
mudslides in the Campania region of southern Italy killed at least
135 people last week. Experts say uncontrolled deforestation and
illegal construction work are partly blamed for the disaster.
</P>
<P>
About 50 percent of Italian territory faces some form of
landslide, flooding or other danger, said the DS environment
spokeswoman Fulvia Bandoli.
</P>
<P>
"A single Environment and Land Ministry, with power to invest
in and monitor land protection, would make sure land policy does
not get swept under the carpet," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Vote Counting in Philippines at Slow Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Official vote counting is continuing
Tuesday across the Philippines, but the pace is very slow.
</P>
<P>
The early partial results provided by the Commission on
Elections early Tuesday Morning cannot show significantly who is
really leading in the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
But the latest unofficial partial results provided by the
Namfrel (National Citizens Movement for Free Elections) show that
Vice President Joseph Estrada, candidate of the Laban ng
Makabayang masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipinos Masses)
is leading in the presidential race with 21,071 votes.
</P>
<P>
He is followed by Emilio Osmena, candidate of the Progressive
Movement for Devolution of Initiative, with 16,941 votes. Former
Manila mayor Alfredo Lim of the Liberal Party trailed third with
9,572 votes.
</P>
<P>
Other presidential candidates include Speaker Jose de Venecia,
who was anointed by President Fidel Ramos as the standard bearer
of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party, and senator Raul Roco of Aksyon
Demokratiko (Democratic Action).
</P>
<P>
The Namfrel is the sole non-government organization authorized
to conduct the unofficial quick count.
</P>
<P>
Official vote counting started immediately after the voting
closed at 15:00 (0700 GMT) Monday. After the counting at the
precinct level, election inspectors will turn over the election
returns to the municipal or city level.
</P>
<P>
The total election returns will be recorded and tabulated and
then given to the provincial level.
</P>
<P>
The forms will then be forwarded to the House of
Representatives for the counting for the presidential and vice
presidential positions, while the Commission on Elections will
count the votes for the congressional posts.
</P>
<P>
The process is expected to take four weeks. But the Namfrel can
release the unofficial final results within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Voting for Monday's national and local elections was held in a
"generally peaceful and orderly manner" with a heavy voter turnout
across the country except for some areas where polling was marred
by violence and election irregularities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commission on Elections, about 80 percent of
the 34 million voters turned out and cast their ballots to choose
a president, a vice president, 12 out of 24 senators, 260 members
of the House of Representatives and more than 17,000 local
officials and councilors.
</P>
<P>
The voting was "generally peaceful and orderly", the Commission
on Elections said.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures showed that a total of 13 people were killed
all over the country in Monday's voting, bringing to 49 the death
toll in election-related violence incidents since election
campaigns began in February.
</P>
<P>
However, compared with the previous elections including those
held in 1992 and 1995, the polls may be the most peaceful and
orderly in the country's election history, poll watchers said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 elections, about 169 people were killed in
election- related violence while in the 1995 senate elections 210
people died.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
