<HEADLINE> Exports From Philippine Economic Zones Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Exports receipts from the
Philippines' economic zones in the first three months of this year
reached 2.9 billion U.S. dollars, up 22 percent from the year-ago
level, according to the Philippine Economic Zone Authority (PEZA).
</P>
<P>
The PEZA said in a report published Tuesday that the exports
from the economic zones accounted for almost one half of the
country's total exports of 6.8 billion dollars in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The report showed exports from the privately-owned special
economic zones outpacing the government-run zones.
</P>
<P>
The exports from the more than 50 privately-owned economic
zones stood at 1.8 billion dollars during the period under review,
while the four government-run zones registered 1.1 billion dollars
in export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Among the four government-run economic zones, the Baguio Export
Processing Zone remains the biggest exporter with 379 million
dollars in export receipts.
</P>
<P>
The exports from the economic zones are expected to move up
further as the peso's depreciation has helped in the
competitiveness in the pricing of the country's exports in the
world market, the PEZA said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government began to establish economic zones in
the 1960s, which have become a major foreign exchange earner for
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
