<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children Suffering from Asthma Treated in Salt Room </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Five-year-old Xu Zhenqi was all
amazement and excitement when he first stepped into the
room. "Woo, it's all salt," the boy exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
Little Zhenqi's mother liked the room, too, for a different
reason. "Since moving into this salt room, Zhenqi's asthma has
gotten much better," she said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
The salt room, specially designed for treating children
suffering asthma in the Children's Hospital in this capital of
northeast China's Liaoning Province, has become very popular among
children and their parents since it opened a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The walls and floor of the airtight room are covered with salt,
said Wu Ying, head of the hospital. Retaining a certain
temperature and moisture, the room is filled with salt mist
emitted from a computer-controlled generator, making the
micro-weather parameters in the room equivalent or close to those
in a natural cave.
</P>
<P>
A non-medicinal therapy, Wu explained, the room works with the
salt mist entering the patient's bronchiole, enhancing the surface
tension of pulmonary alveoli, dissolving phlegm and thus improving
the ventilating function of the lungs.
</P>
<P>
While being treated in the room, children can play games, do
reading or watch TV just as in any ordinary room. One course
of treatment, taking 21 consecutive days with one hour each day,
yields apparent positive effects.
</P>
<P>
Asthma is a common disease among Chinese children, and a
national survey of 14-year-olds put the incidence of asthma at
0.5-to-2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The salt-room technology cost more than 400,000 yuan (about
48,200 U.S. dollars), according to Wu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
