<HEADLINE> China Eyes Closer Cooperation with Germany in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Xie Zhenhua, who heads the Chinese
State Environmental Protection Administration, said here Monday
that he saw great potential for closer cooperation between China
and Germany in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Xie, who is on a three-day visit to Germany, made the remarks
during his talks with German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel Monday
in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
With environmental protection to become a key investment area
in China in coming few years, China represented an important
market for advanced environmental protection technologies that
could be offered by German enterprises, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel meanwhile noted that both smaller and large German
enterprises had great interest in participating in environmental
protection projects in China. The German and Chinese economies
supplemented each other quite well especially in this area, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister also said that Germany would make
it a priority for the European Union (EU) to further improve ties
with Asia after Bonn assumes the rotating presidency of the EU in
January 1999. The relations with China would play a particularly
important role in this regard, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Government Initiates Forceful Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Prime Minister Radu
Vasile Monday publicly supported the measure taken by the Finance
Ministry against the National Power Company RENEL which had large
debts to the state.
</P>
<P>
According to the national news agency Rompres, Finance Ministry
late last week froze the accounts of RENEL after it proved
incapable of paying its 235 million US dollars debt to the state.
The Prime Minister stated earlier that he had not been informed
about this decision and did not comment on it untill Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was primarily caused by RENEL's failure to keep up
with the payment installments, as State Secretary with the Finance
Ministry Corneliu Gorcea stated.
</P>
<P>
RENEL benefited during the former government from a
re-scheduling of its debts on a two year term (1998-1999).
However, RENEL paid 11,6 million US dollars in the first
trimester, which represents only 5 percent of the total debt.
RENEL was also exempted from the payment of 55,8 million US
dollars in penalties.
</P>
<P>
Authorized sources at RENEL stated that the company was not
able to pay its debts due to the fact that numerous companies were
indebted to RENEL and not paying their debts.
</P>
<P>
State Secretary Gorcea stated that the measure taken was legal
and the accounts of RENEL will be unfrozen only if the government
assumes responsibility.
</P>
<P>
He warned that same measure would be applied to other
autonomous administrations and trade companies which had large
debts to the state. "Besides freezing their accounts, the Ministry
of Finance will initiate forceful measures concerning certain
assets of the debtors," Gorcea stressed.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that the 1998 state budget draft specified an
amount of 517 million US dollars to be collected from debtors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Purchases of U.S. Treasuries fall in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Total foreign net purchases of
U.S. Treasuries fell to 183.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 from
232.2 billion dollars in 1996 on reduced purchases activity
especially in the official institution sector.
</P>
<P>
Demand declined most notably in the second half of the year,
with only 36 percent occurring in this period, corresponding to
Asia's economic crisis, the U.S. Bond Market Association said in a
report on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Official purchases by foreign official institutions, including
national central banks and monetary authorities fell 49.8 percent
to 43.1 billion dollars in 1997 from 85.8 billion dollars in 1996,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
But purchases by foreign private investors fell only 5.5
percent to 140.1 billion dollars from 148.3 billion dollars a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Declines in this sector were not as significant, said the
report, as the financial crisis resulting from Asia's economic
woes prompted some foreign private investors to seek safety in
U.S. Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
Buying activity in Europe soared to 146.2 billion dollars from
118.8 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Japanese purchases stood at 20.4 billion dollars from 41.4
billion dollars in 1996, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
