<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Buy More U.S. Bonds, Debt Securities in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign purchases of U.S.
corporate bonds and debt securities issued by U.S. federal
agencies and government-owned corporations reached record levels
of 86.4 billion U.S. dollars and 49.6 billion dollars respectively
in 1997, according to the U.S. Bond Market Association (BMA).
</P>
<P>
U.S. bond sales to foreigners rose from 83.7 billion dollars in
1996 while U.S. debt securities sales stood at 41.7 billion
dollars in 1996, the BMA said in its latest report.
</P>
<P>
Continued demand from Europe and a sharp rise in buying from
Latin America helped offset weak demand in Asia for U.S. corporate
bonds while the Latin American and Caribbean region bought the
largest amount of U.S. federal agency debt in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The BMA represents securities firms and banks which underwrite,
trade and sell debt securities both domestically and
internationally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
