<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cities Behind States in Reducing Welfare Backlog: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- It is more difficult for city
dwellers in the United States to shift from welfare to work than
their suburban and rural counterparts, according to a study
released by the Brookings Institution Monday.
</P>
<P>
The study of 23 cities and urban counties found two-thirds of
cities lagged behind their respective states in reducing welfare
caseloads between 1994 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the city of Bridgeport reduced its welfare
caseload 70 percent more slowly than did Connecticut. San
Francisco reduced its welfare caseload at a pace nearly three
times that of California.
</P>
<P>
The study focused on Northeastern and Midwestern communities.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that the pace at which a city reduced its
welfare rate appeared to closely correlate with the extent of
poverty in that city. For example, San Francisco with a relatively
low rate of high poverty areas, cut its welfare caseload swiftly.
</P>
<P>
However, in St. Louis in Missouri, where more than 25 percent
of residents live in areas of high poverty, the city cut its
welfare caseloads 40 percent more slowly than did the state.
</P>
<P>
Bruce Katz, director of the institution's Center on Urban
Policy, said that while the study confirms what many people
thought to be the case -- that poverty is most heavily
concentrated in urban centers -- it also points out that new
strategies should be developed to get urban people to the
entry-level jobs that often lie outside the urban core. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
