<DOCNO> XIE19980512.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Warns Sri Lanka's Aging Population Poses Perils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's population is
aging faster than any country in the world, a report form the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) says on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report warns that unless dramatic changes are made in the
country's pension system, the fiscal burden of supporting Sri
Lanka's future elderly population will become unbearable.
</P>
<P>
The reports estimates that in the next two decades, the number
of elderly in the country will double, and that by 2025, the
country will be the only "non-high income" country with an elderly
population representing more than 20 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Suggestions to avert this crisis include increasing the
country's retirement age and encouraging more women to seek paid
employment. "Sri Lanka has a narrow window of opportunity now to
develop policies to avert the potentially negative impacts of an
aging population on the country's economy and society," the
report says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
