<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Report on Sanctions Waiver for Europeans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Stated Department
Monday denied that it had indicated to the European Union that
Washington might grant European firms a sanctions waiver relating
to business with Iran.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has received no
recommendation on whether to impose sanctions against three
foreign companies for investing in Iran's energy sector, said
State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
He described as "absolutely untrue" a Financial Times report
Monday that Albright had indicated to European Trade Commissioner
Sir Leon Brittan that Washington might grant European firms a
sanctions waiver before or during a U.S.-European Union summit
next week.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Albright has not received a recommendation yet on
this subject," Rubin said, reiterating that a decision was close.
</P>
<P>
"It is certainly true that we are nearing a decision on that
and that we have been consulting with European governments,
including this past weekend in London, about policies toward Iran
and related issues," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
A 2 billion U.S. dollar deal was struck by France's Total,
Russia's Gazprom and Malaysia's Petronas to develop a major
Iranian oil-field last year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been reviewing it. The deal violates the U.S.
Iran-Libya Sanctions Act, which was enacted in 1996. It punishes
companies investing more than 20 million U.S. dollars a year in
the oil or gas industries in those two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
