<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises Against Mark, Falls Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose against the
mark and other European currencies Monday as fewer traders
believed that Germany would raise interest rates soon.
</P>
<P>
The dollar edged lower against the yen on renewed fears of
intervention to back up the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar bought 1.7766 marks, up
from 1.7701. The dollar was quoted at 132.75 yen, down from 132.83
late Friday.
</P>
<P>
Investors had expected Germany to raise interest rates to
maintain continent-wide currency stability.
</P>
<P>
However, economic data released last week and remarks by German
bank officials did not show Germany would make an interest rate
hike.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.4850 Swiss francs, up from 1.4800; 5.9580 French francs, up from
5.9325; 1,752.00 Italian lire, up from 1,744.00; and 1.4352
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4363.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6297 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6393 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
