<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright to Seek to Overcome Differences With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright will meet with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
Wednesday in Washington to find ways for breaking the deadlocked
peace process in the Middle East, the State Department announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary Albright just got off the phone with Prime Minister
Netanyahu and they agreed to meet here in Washington on Wednesday
to discuss ways in which we can overcome remaining differences"
between Israel and the Palestinians, spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the announcement after Albright held talks at the
White House with President Bill Clinton, National Security Adviser
Sandy Berger and U.S. special Middle East envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said in a written statement that the purpose of
Albright's discussion with the Israeli leader "will be to seek to
overcome the remaining differences so we proceed immediately with
accelerated permanent status talks."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Albright would report to him after her talks with
Netanyahu to determine whether there was a basis for launching a
peace conference like that of the aborted Washington summit,
originally scheduled to take place right on Monday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that the
president wanted the Israelis and Palestinians "to get on with
serious business of addressing the gaps and differences that
exits."
</P>
<P>
Last week, Clinton invited Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to Washington for a summit, which he said would
jump-start to the final status talks as Israel had suggested, but
it would happen only when Israel accepts a U.S. proposal to make a
further pullback from 13.1 percent of the land on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has rejected the invitation, saying the time had not
ripe to accept the U.S. proposal as it would endanger its
security. The scheduled summit has thus to be canceled.
</P>
<P>
At the White House meeting earlier in the day, special envoy
Ross gave the president his assessment of the situation in the
Middle East after his weekend failed shuttle diplomacy between
Netanyahu and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
"It was an assessment of whether we are and what we should do,"
an administration official said. "Obviously no one here wants this
to be the end of the process." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
